{[%evp 0,8,16,29,23,11,11,2,2,2,66]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {
Let's have a look at the most relevant sidelines to avoid any unpleasant
surprises!} g6 (4... d5 {has never been tried at GM level, but is quite
popular at an amateur level. Black directly attempts to strike in the centre,
though the opening of the position should favour the side having a lead in
development (White). White has a couple of promising options, but I think that}
5. Nxc6 $5 {is the easiest choice.} (5. Bb5 $5) 5... bxc6 6. exd5 Qxd5 (6...
cxd5 7. Bb5+ {and Black either loses a pawn or the right to castle.}) 7. Bd3 $5
Qxg2 (7... Qe5+ 8. Be3 $1 Qxb2 (8... Bc5 9. O-O Bxe3 10. Re1 $36 {[%csl Re8]})
9. Nd2) (7... Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ye1g1] and White is
just better.}) 8. Qe2+ Kd8 9. Be4 Qg4 10. Bf3 Qe6 11. Be3 $40 {[%csl Rd8][%cal
Yb1c3,Ye1c1] followed by Nc3 and 0-0-0.}) (4... Be7 {doesn't challenge White's
centre and gives White easy play, e.g.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 $6 (5... d6 $16 {is more
wise perhaps.}) 6. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 (7... Ng8 {[%csl Rg8]}) 8. Nxd5 cxd5
9. Qxd5 Rb8 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Qd4 Bxg2 12. Rg1 {[%csl Rg7] and White has a
crushing position.}) (4... Nxd4 5. Qxd4 Qf6 6. e5 Qb6 7. Qxb6 (7. Qf4 $2 d5
$132 {Ortiz Suarez-Granda Zuniga, Cochabamba 2013.}) 7... axb6 8. Nc3 {[%csl
Rc7,Ge5][%cal Yc1d2,Yc3d5,Yc3b5,Ye1c1,Yh1e1] just looks better for White
thanks to his pawn on e5. White has an overwhelming score in the database.}) (
4... Qh4 {This used to be a very popular choice for Black but is hardly seen
any longer these days, as the following lines lead to a clearly better
position for White:} 5. Nc3 $1 Bb4 (5... Bc5 6. Be3 $16 {and the queen on h4
makes no sense.}) 6. Be2 $1 Qxe4 (6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qxe4 8. Nb5 Kd8 {
transposes.}) 7. Ndb5 Bxc3+ (7... Kd8 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 {leads to the same
as well.}) 8. bxc3 Kd8 9. O-O {[%csl Rd8] and despite being a pawn down, White
has a massive initiative as Black's king is stuck in the centre.} Nf6 (9... d6
$2 {is met by} 10. Nxd6 $1 {, e.g.} cxd6 11. Qxd6+ Ke8 12. Bf3 Qe6 13. Qc7 Nge7
14. Ba3 Qd7 15. Qg3 Nf5 16. Qf4 Nce7 17. Rfe1 h5 18. Rad1 Qb5 19. Qg5 Be6 20.
Bxe7 f6 21. Bxf6 Kf7 22. Bxg7 {1-0 Smeets-Pliester, Netherlands 2003.}) 10. Re1
({Another possibility is} 10. Rb1 a6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 Re8 13. Bf3 Qg6 14.
Bf4 $44 {with good compensation for the pawn in Van der Wiel-Pliester,
Enschede 2003.}) 10... Re8 11. Bg5 {[%cal Yd1d2,Ye2f3] and White's position is
very easy to play.}) (4... Nge7 {with the idea of trading one pair of knights
and bring the other to c6.} 5. Nc3 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 Bb4 8. Bd2 O-O 9.
O-O-O {with very comfortable play for White, e.g.} d6 10. a3 (10. Qg3 $5 {
[%cal Yf2f4]}) 10... Ba5 11. Qg3 f5 12. f4 fxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 14. Rxd2 Bf5 15.
Bc4+ Kh8 {Morozevich-Hjartarson, Berlin blitz 2015 and now} 16. Re1 $16 {
[%cal Ye4c3]}) 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 ({Another approach is} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bc4 $5)
6... Nf6 ({Once Black commits himself to an early ...d6 I like the setup with
Be3,Qd2 and 0-0-0 etc. A good example} 6... d6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. f3 O-O 9. O-O-O
Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. g4 c5 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Bh6 Rfd8 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h4 Bxa2
{was played in Najer-Mamedyarov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 and had White continued
his attacking plans} 16. h5 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Yd2h6,Yh5g6] the game would
probably have been finished much earlier.}) (6... Nge7 $6 7. Qd2 O-O (7... d6
8. O-O-O Be6 9. h4 Qd7 10. h5 O-O-O {Glek-Granda Zuniga, El Sauzal 2006} 11.
Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Nd5 $16 {[%cal Yf1b5,Ye3g5,Yh5h6] and Black is under heavy
pressure.}) 8. O-O-O d6 (8... d5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bc5 $1 $16) 9. h4 h5 (9...
Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qd2 Be6 13. f4 {[%cal Yh4h5] gives White a
massive attack.}) 10. f3 Ne5 11. Bh6 b5 (11... a6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Be2 {
[%cal Yg3g4,Yf3f4] and White is having a great time, while Black's counterplay
isn't visible.}) 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Bxb5 Rb8 14. g4 hxg4 15. h5 Rh8 16. f4 $18 {
and White has a crushing attack in Kobalia-Mamedyarov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013.})
7. Nxc6 $1 ({I like this more than} 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O Re8 9. f3 {which gives
Black excellent results in the database after} d5 $1 $132) 7... bxc6 (7... dxc6
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. O-O-O+ Ke8 10. h3 $16) 8. e5 Ng8 (8... Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10.
Qxd5 Rb8 11. O-O-O {and Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the
pawn.}) 9. f4 {Other moves have been tried here as well, but the text is most
consistent} Ne7 (9... d6 10. Qf3 Ne7 {leads to the same.}) 10. Qf3 d6 11. Bc4
$1 ({In my opinion more accurate than} 11. O-O-O {when Black might consider}
Be6 $5) 11... Nf5 (11... O-O 12. O-O-O Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 Nf5 15. Bf2 {
and White is clearly better. A nice model game:} Qb8 16. Ne4 Qb4 17. Rhe1 Rab8
18. b3 Qa3+ 19. Kb1 h6 20. g4 Ne7 21. Nf6+ Kf7 22. f5 dxe5 23. fxg6+ Kxf6 24.
Qh5 Nxg6 25. Rf1 Ke7 26. Qxg6 Bf6 27. Bh4 {1-0 Erwich-Noetzel, Germany 2015.})
12. Bf2 dxe5 (12... d5 {runs into} 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bxd5 Rb8 15. Bc6+ Kf8 16.
Qa3+ Kg8 17. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd8] and White regains his invested material.}) 13.
Qxc6+ (13. Rd1 $1 {might actually be better, e.g.} Nd4 (13... Bd7 14. fxe5 Bxe5
15. g4 Qe7 16. gxf5 Bxc3+ 17. Kf1 $1 $18) 14. Qe4 $1 Bf5 15. Rxd4 Bxe4 16.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Nxe4 exf4 18. Bc5 $18) 13... Bd7 14. Qc5 $16 {
Grandelius-Sandipan, Abu Dhabi 2015.} *

