{[%evp 0,13,24,24,28,28,18,14,-4,4,37,37,64,81,65,23]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 ({Once this system was considered as a serious
alternative to the main continuations, starting with 4...Nf6 and 4...Bc5.
However, since the theory is developing this mysterious provocation isn't that
popular any longer as it used to be. The alternative} 5... Be7 {has been
examined in the next chapter.}) 6. Be3 Bb6 (6... Nf6 $2 {loses a piece after}
7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bxc5 $18) 7. Nf5 $1 {Forcing the exchange of dark-squared
bishops and preparing a setup with pawns on c4 and e4 and knights on c3 and e3.
} Bxe3 ({Another critical branch is} 7... g6 8. Bxb6 axb6 9. Ne3 Nf6 10. f3 (
10. Nd2 $6 d5 $1 {is very comfortable for Black.}) 10... O-O (10... Qe7 11. Be2
$5 (11. c4 Qb4+ (11... Qc5 12. Kf2 $16 {[%cal Yb1c3]}) 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
d6 14. Nc3 Kd8 {has been seen in numerous games. White's edge is beyond any
doubt, but Black is quite solid.}) 11... O-O (11... Qc5 12. Qd2 O-O ({In the
following encounter Black's play was completely pointless:} 12... h5 $6 13. Na3
$1 Qe7 $6 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Ne5 16. d6 Qxd6 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18. Nb5 Ke7 19.
a4 {with a strategically hopeless position for Black in Duda-Degraeve,
Chartres 2017.}) 13. c4 {transposes to 11...0-0.}) 12. c4 Qc5 ({The idea of 11.
Be2 is that after} 12... Qb4+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $14 {[%csl Rc7][%cal
Yb1c3] the black king is no longer able to defend c7.}) (12... d6 13. Nc3 $16)
13. Qd2 Nd4 14. Bd1 b5 15. b4 Qe5 16. Nc3 c5 17. Rc1 cxb4 ({One day later in
the same tournament Black went for} 17... b6 $2 18. O-O ({Also possible is} 18.
cxb5 cxb4 19. Ncd5 $16) 18... bxc4 {and now in Sevian-Bacallao Alonso,
Varadero 2016 White could have obtained a huge advantage by means of} 19. Nxc4
$1 Qe6 20. Na4 $1 $16) 18. Ncd5 Nxd5 $6 ({Probably Black better refrains from
trading the knights too early. Better is} 18... d6 19. O-O Be6 {when White is
still somewhat better, but not so clear at all. The point is that} 20. f4 $2 {
fails to} Nxe4 $1 $19) 19. Nxd5 d6 20. O-O Ne6 (20... f5 21. f4 Qg7 22. Re1
bxc4 23. Rxc4 Nc6 24. Bb3 $16) 21. cxb5 $18 {Xiong-Gomez Garrido, Varadero
2016.}) 11. c4 {Black has to make an important decision here. Playing slowly
leads to a clearly inferior structure as White has a nice grip on the central
squares. However, the dynamical approaches (both 11...Nh5, intending f5 & 11...
d5) aren't solving Black's problems either.} Nh5 (11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxe4 13.
fxe4 $1 ({Critical. White better refrains from entering the complications
arising from} 13. dxc6 $6 Qh4+ 14. g3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 {which has been played in
a couple of games, but it seems to me that after both taking on g3 or on h1
Black's position is easier to play with such an exposed king in the centre.})
13... Qh4+ 14. Kd2 $1 ({I find this more logical than} 14. Ke2 {which was
played in Oleksienko-Godena, Gjakova 2016. The white king is safer on the
queenside and on e2 it obstructs the light-squared bishop.}) 14... Qxe4 15. Bd3
$1 (15. Qb3 $2 {was played in Zierk-Safarli, chess.com INT 2019 and now Black
should have played} Re8 $1 {preventing White from developing with moves like
Bd3 or Nc3. After} 16. Na3 Qd4+ 17. Qd3 Qf4 $1 18. Re1 (18. dxc6 $2 Bf5 $1 {
is harakiri.}) 18... Nb4 19. Qc3 Nxd5 20. Qc4 Re4 {and White remains under
pressure.}) (15. Qc2 $2 Qf4 $1 16. Qc4 Nd4 17. Nc3 Re8 18. Re1 {was seen in
Oglaza-Cuenca Jimenez, Caleta 2018 and now the following line is not so easy
to calculate in advance:} Bf5 19. Bd3 Qf2+ 20. Re2 Nxe2 21. Ncd1 Bxd3 22. Qxd3
Rxe3 23. Nxf2 Rxd3+ 24. Nxd3 Nd4 $19 {and Black is a healthy pawn up.}) (15.
Nc3 $6 Qd4+ 16. Ke2 Qf4 17. dxc6 bxc6 $1 {and Black stays in the game,} ({
but not} 17... Re8 $2 {which was played in Sochacki-Mons, Maribor 2012 and now
White has a surprising way to clinch a decisive advantage:} 18. Ncd5 $1 Bg4+
19. Ke1 $1 Rxe3+ 20. Be2 $18)) 15... Qd4 (15... Qb4+ $2 {just enables White to
consolidate with} 16. Nc3 Ne5 17. Qb3 $18 {and White is winning in Vovk,
A-D'Amore, Gallipoli 2016.}) 16. Qb3 $1 ({Quite an effective consolidating
move, whereas} 16. dxc6 $6 Qxb2+ 17. Nc2 Rd8 {leads to unnecessary
complications.}) 16... Re8 17. Re1 (17. dxc6 $2 Rxe3 18. Re1 Rxe1 19. Kxe1 {
was played in Zierk-Grover, chess.com INT 2019 when Black has several winning
continuations, of which I consider} Bf5 $1 {as the most convincing. For
instance} 20. Bxf5 Re8+ 21. Kf1 Qf4+ 22. Qf3 (22. Kg1 Re1#) 22... Qc1+ 23. Kf2
Qe1#) 17... Ne5 18. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ya3c2]} ({Inferior is the inclusion of} 18.
Qc3 $2 Qf4 $1 19. Na3 {as played in Zumsande-Jones, Douglas 2015 and here
Black could have seized the initiative by means of} Ra5 $1) 18... Nxd3 (18...
Bd7 19. Nac2 Qf4 20. Rf1 {and White went on to convert his material plus in
Perunovic-Stojanovic, Ruma 2017.}) 19. Nac2 $1 (19. Qxd3 Qxb2+ 20. Nac2 {
as played in Danin-Zeller, Wunsiedel 2016 also favours White, but after} Qe5
$14 {Black has some hopes to generate counterplay.}) 19... Qf4 20. Qxd3 $18 {
and White is winning. An important detail is that} Bf5 {can be met with} 21.
Rf1 Qh6 22. Rxf5 gxf5 23. Qxf5) (11... d6 12. Nc3 Nh5 13. Qd2 Ng7 (13... Be6
14. O-O-O Ne5 15. Kb1 f5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Ned5 c6 {was seen in
Brandenburg-L'Ami, Dieren 2007 and here} 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 19. Qxd6 $18 {would
have been decisive.}) 14. Bd3 Ne5 {was played in Lagno-Ovod, Chita 2015 and
here I would rather go for} 15. O-O $16 {with similar play as in other lines.})
({Pointless is} 11... Qe7 $6 12. Nc3 Qc5 13. Qd2 Nb4 14. Rc1 Qe5 15. a3 Nc6 16.
Ncd5 Ne8 17. Bd3 d6 18. O-O $16 {and even though Black went on to win in
Rublevsky-Sokolov, Kragujevac 2009 his position is absolutely horrible.}) 12.
Qd2 f5 {The principled continuation, but with precise play White retains a big
advantage. The alternatives are simply too passive:} (12... Na5 13. Na3 $1 ({
Of course, not} 13. Nc3 $2 {in view of} Nb3 $1) 13... d6 14. g3 $16 {with a
clear edge for White in Chigaev-Gasanov, St Petersburg 2013. White is going to
follow up with Bg2 and 0-0, while Black is lacking counterplay against pawns
on c4 and d4.}) (12... Ng7 13. Bd3 d6 14. O-O f5 15. f4 Be6 16. Nc3 Qf6 17.
Rae1 Rae8 18. b3 fxe4 19. Bxe4 Nf5 {and now in Deac-Tomazini, Budapest 2018
White could have increased his advantage with} 20. Ned5 Qd8 21. g4 $1 {
intending to bring the pawn to g5, preparing Nf6 at a suitable moment.}) 13.
exf5 $1 (13. Nc3 $6 {is less convincing, because of} fxe4 (13... f4 $2 14. Ned5
Qh4+ $2 (14... d6 15. O-O-O {[%cal Yc1b1,Yf1e2]}) 15. Qf2 Qd8 16. Nb5 $18 {
and Black is lost in Yu Yangyi-Bu Xiangzhi, Doha blitz 2016.}) 14. Nxe4 {
was played in Recio-Girones Barrios, Cocoa Beach 2017 and now after the simple}
d6 {Black obtains reasonable play.}) 13... Qh4+ (13... Re8 14. Nc3 Qh4+ {
was seen in Gusain-Sanikidze, Amol 2018 where White went for 15.g3, which is
also good, but in my opinion simpler is} 15. Kd1 $1 {with the point that after}
Ng3 16. hxg3 Qxh1 17. Kc2 $18 {compared with that game White has an extra
g-pawn.}) 14. Qf2 Qd4 15. Nc3 $1 Re8 16. Ne4 $1 Nf6 (16... gxf5 17. Nxf5 Qxf2+
18. Kxf2 $16 {and White has an extra pawn.}) (16... Ra3 $2 {looks spectacular,
but was easily refuted after} 17. Nd5 $1 Qe5 18. fxg6 Nf6 19. Qh4 Nh5 20. Qxh5
{1-0 Antal-Cruz, Barcelona 2017.}) 17. Bd3 d5 {and so far we have been
following the game Pichot-Flores, Buenos Aires 2017. Now the simple} 18. Nxf6+
Qxf6 19. O-O {gives White a winning advantage. After} Qd4 20. Rfe1 {Black
can't play} Qxd3 {in view of} 21. Rad1) (7... Qf6 $6 {is a rare move and can
best be met by} 8. Na3 $1 Nge7 9. Nb5 Ba5 (9... Kd8 10. Qd2 Bxe3 11. Nxe3 $16 {
wasn't much fun for Black either in Jarmula-Chylewski, Graz 2017.}) 10. Nxe7
Qxe7 11. Bd3 d6 12. O-O O-O 13. a4 {and White is just better in
Lagno-Stefanova, Tashkent 2013. Even simplified position after} Bb6 14. Bxb6
axb6 15. f4 $16 {[%csl Gb5,Rc7][%cal Yd3c2,Yd1d3,Ya1e1] Black is suffering
from some structural problems on the queenside.}) 8. Nxe3 Nf6 (8... d6 9. c4 (
9. g3 {is possible here as well, but then Black might still consider a more
active way of developing his knight, e.g.} Nf6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. c4 $14) 9...
Nge7 (9... Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. f3 {transposes to the Main Line with 8...d6.})
10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bd3 ({The radical} 11. g4 $6 {(stopping ...f7-f5)} Ng6 12. Qd2
{was played in Zhou,-Bok, Porto Carras 2010, but now after} Qh4 $15 {Black has
a firm grip on the dark squares.}) (11. Be2 $6 {allows} f5 $1 12. exf5 Nxf5 13.
Nxf5 Bxf5 $132 {with excellent play for Black in Nepomniachtchi-Kramnik, Sochi
blitz 2014.}) 11... f5 $5 (11... Kh8 {has been played in quite a couple of
games, but it seems Black can play ...f7-f5 without this preparatory move.} 12.
O-O f5 13. f4 Be6 14. Qd2 Qd7 15. Rae1 $14 {Amonatov-Sakaev, St Petersburg 2015
}) 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Bxf5 Bxf5 14. Qd5+ ({Perhaps White shouldn't play in a
very principled way and instead just go for a slight plus, e.g.} 14. O-O $5 Qd7
15. Qd2 Rae8 16. f4 Kh8 {(anyway...)} 17. Rae1 Ne7 {as played in
Tari-Johannessen, Norway 2018. Probably it's a good moment start expanding on
the kingside with} 18. h3 $5 $14 {[%cal Yg2g4,Yb2b3]}) 14... Kh8 15. Nxf5 Qf6 (
15... Nb4 16. Qd2 Rxf5 17. O-O Qd7 18. Rae1 $14 {Belikov-Yandemirov, Alushta
2012.}) 16. O-O ({A new idea is} 16. O-O-O $5 $146 Qxf5 17. Qxf5 Rxf5 18. f3
$14 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Yb2b3,Yf5f7] followed by doubling rooks on the e-file.
Only White can be slightly better, even though it might not be anything
special, like in the lines with 16.0-0.}) 16... Qxf5 17. Qxf5 Rxf5 18. f4 g6 (
18... Kg8 19. Rae1 Kf8 20. Re4 (20. g4 $5) 20... Re8 21. Rfe1 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Nb4
$1 {[%cal Yd6d5,Yb4d3]} 23. b3 d5 24. cxd5 {½-½ Nasuta-Postny, Zagreb 2017.})
19. Rae1 Kg7 20. Nd5 Rf7 {and soon a draw had been agreed in
Khairullin-Alekseev, St Petersburg 2012.}) (8... Nge7 {Since Black has
committed his knight to e7, I think the setup with} 9. g3 $5 {makes quite some
sense.} (9. c4 d6 {would transpose to positions examined with 8...d6.}) 9... d6
10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Kh8 12. Nd2 ({White could also start with} 12. f4 {which
comes down to the same after} f5 13. Nd2) 12... f5 13. f4 $1 ({In
Savchenko-Adams, Moscow blitz 2007, White started with} 13. exf5 {but I would
prefer maintaining the tension for a while.}) 13... fxe4 (13... Be6 14. exf5 (
14. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ya1e1]}) 14... Nxf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Qb3 Rb8 17. Rae1 Qd7
18. Nf3 (18. Re3 $5 {[%cal Yf1e1] looks like a simpler way for White to
proceed.}) 18... Bd3 19. Rf2 Rfe8 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Ng5 $6 (21. Qd1 $14) 21...
Qe1+ 22. Bf1 h6 23. Nf3 {was seen in Vidit-Abdulla, Chengdu 2017 and now
according to the silicon monster Black could have maintained the balance with}
(23. Kg2 $5) 23... Qc1 $1 $132 {In any case, from a practical point of view I
wouldn't recommend White allowing the Black queen from entering via the e-file.
}) 14. Nxe4 Nf5 15. Re1 Nce7 (15... Nxe3 16. Rxe3 Bf5 17. Qb3 Rb8 18. Ng5 Qd7
19. Rae1 {just with simple moves White has obtained a huge advantage. The
following game nicely shows how White should convert his positional dominance
into a full point:} h6 20. Ne6 Rfe8 21. Qd5 Bxe6 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Rxe6 Ne7 $2
({Necessary is} 23... Re8 {though after} 24. Rxe8+ Qxe8 25. Kf2 $16 {[%csl Rb7,
Rc6,Rh8][%cal Yg2e4,Yb2b4,Yh2h4,Ya2a4] Black is awaiting a long torture.}) 24.
Qe4 Ng8 25. Qf5 Rd8 26. Be4 g6 27. Qxg6 d5 28. Bd3 d4 29. Rf6 Nxf6 30. Qxf6+
Kg8 31. Bc4+ Kh7 32. Bf7 Rg8 33. Bxg8+ Kxg8 34. Qg6+ {1-0 Aryan-Rajdeep,
Ahmedabad 2017.}) 16. Nxf5 (16. Ng5 {is likely to transpose.}) 16... Nxf5 17.
Ng5 h6 18. Ne6 ({The piece sacrifice} 18. Qh5 $6 g6 19. Qxg6 hxg5 {as tried in
Kovalev-Mikaelyan, Jerusalem 2015, is also worth considering but there is no
need for White entering the complications.}) 18... Bxe6 19. Rxe6 $16 {and
White is clearly better in Matlakov-Postny, St Petersburg 2018 thanks to the
control of the open e-file.}) 9. f3 (9. Bd3 $6 {should be met by} d5 $1 {
not giving White a second chance playing c3-c4.}) 9... O-O 10. c4 d6 11. Nc3
Nd7 {Other moves have been tried here as well, but they don't change the
character of the play.} 12. Be2 ({I believe White should aim for a simple
setup with castling kingside and hence I would like to recommend. The
alternative} 12. Qd2 {possibly transposes, although in quite a number of games
White players have played this move with the intention of castling queenside.})
(12. Bd3 Nc5 13. O-O Nxd3 14. Qxd3 $14 {was played in Muzychuk, A-Korneev,
Linares 2018, but since White has a pleasant space advantage I would prefer
keeping some minor pieces on the board.}) 12... Nc5 13. O-O a5 ({Securing the
knight on c5, without being pushed back by b2-b4. The immediate} 13... f5 $2
14. exf5 Bxf5 {was seen in Van Kampen-Babula, Warsaw 2013 and now White could
have obtained a huge advantage by means of} 15. b4 $1 Qe8 (15... Ne6 16. f4
Ned4 17. Bh5 {and Black has serious coordination problems, in view of threats
b4-b5 and g2-g4.}) (15... Nxb4 16. Nxf5 Rxf5 17. Qb1 $18 {is the tactical
justification.}) 16. Ncd5 (16. Nxf5 Rxf5 17. bxc5 Qe3+ 18. Kh1 Qxc3 19. cxd6
cxd6 20. Rb1 $16 {is also great for White.}) 16... Ne6 17. f4 $16 {and White
has a massive advantage.}) 14. Qd2 Be6 (14... Bd7 15. f4 Ne7 16. Bf3 Bc6 17.
Rae1 {As so often in these position Black is lacking an active plan.} Kh8 18.
Nc2 Ng6 19. g3 Ne7 20. Bg2 f5 21. Nd4 Bxe4 22. Bxe4 fxe4 23. Nxe4 Nf5 24. Nxf5
Nxe4 25. Rxe4 Rxf5 26. Rfe1 {and once again, White controls the only open file:
} Qf8 27. R1e3 h6 28. g4 Rf7 29. f5 Rd7 30. Qe2 Qf6 31. Re6 Qd4 32. Kg2 d5 $2
33. Re8+ Rxe8 34. Rxe8+ Kh7 35. g5 $1 g6 36. Re7+ Rxe7 37. Qxe7+ {
Idani-Gordievsky, Qinhuangdao 2018.}) (14... Ne7 15. f4 ({This makes more
sense than} 15. Rad1 {which was played in Hommeles-Sarakauskas, Baden 2013. In
the ensuing structures where Black meets f2-f4 with ...f7-f5 the white rooks
are best placed on e1 and f1.}) 15... f5 16. Bf3 Bd7 17. Rae1 Kh8 18. exf5 Nxf5
19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Nxe3 21. Rxe3 $14 {Adair-Sarakauskas, England 2018.}) (
14... f5 $2 {is premature, in view of} 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nxf5 Rxf5 17. f4 Kh8
18. Rae1 $16 {Vitoux-Wantiez, Reunion 2007.}) 15. f4 f6 16. Bf3 Qe7 17. Rad1
$16 {Black's position is quite passive, but his next move allows a beautiful
breakthrough:} Qf7 $2 18. e5 $1 f5 (18... dxe5 $2 {runs into} 19. f5 $1 Bc8 20.
Bd5 {and White wins material.}) (18... Bxc4 $2 19. Nxc4 Qxc4 20. Bd5+ $18) (
18... fxe5 19. f5 Bxf5 20. Bd5 Ne6 21. Nxf5 $18) 19. exd6 Rad8 20. Nb5 cxd6 21.
Qc3 $18 {and White is winning in Tari-Esipenko, St Petersburg rapid 2018.} *

