{[%evp 0,10,19,38,25,16,16,15,15,15,81,46,49]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Be7 {A system with a solid reputation, although the ensuing
positions are looking passive for Black.} 6. Nxc6 (6. Bc4 Nf6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8.
e5 {transposes to the Main Line.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bc4 ({Our Main Line is a
direct attempt to punish Black's passive choice. Another setup is} 7. Bd3 d6 (
7... d5 8. O-O (8. e5 $5 {[%csl Rg8] looks also promising.}) 8... Nf6 9. Nd2
O-O {and now in Van der Weide-Van der Wiel, Wijk aan Zee 2006, White could
have obtained a clear advantage by means of} 10. e5 Nd7 11. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rc6,
Ge5]}) 8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1 ({In the majority of games, White started with} 9. Nd2
{but I think So's play at this early stage is simple and instructive.}) 9...
O-O 10. Nd2 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Yd2f3,Yc1f4,Ye4e5]} Re8 11. Nf3 Nd7 12. Bf4
Nc5 13. Bc2 Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ye3c5]} Nd7 16. Ba4 c5 17.
g4 Bg6 18. e5 Rb8 {and now in So-Carlsen, Saint Louis 2017, White started
drifting but with} 19. b3 $1 $16 {White would have retained control over the
position.}) 7... Nf6 (7... d6 8. Qb3 $1 Nf6 9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. Be6 Nxe4 11. Bxc8
Qxc8 12. O-O $16 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Yb1d2] is just better for White, as in
Manca-Tan, Budapest 2017.}) 8. e5 Nd5 (8... Ne4 9. Qf3 $5 (9. O-O O-O 10. Nd2
Nxd2 11. Bxd2 d6 {½-½ Tiviakov-Aronian, Warsaw 2005 isn't a very
inspirational example.}) 9... d5 10. exd6 Nxd6 11. O-O (11. Qxc6+ $6 Bd7 12.
Qc5 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Rb8 {[%csl Rc4,Re1][%cal Yd7b5,Yb8b6] with excellent play.})
11... O-O (11... Nxc4 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qxc4 $14 {with some compensation, but
I would take White here.}) (11... Bb7 12. Ba6 $1 $16 {Jones-Davies, Swansea
2006.}) 12. Bd3 Rb8 13. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7]}) 9. Qg4 (9. Bxd5 cxd5 10. Qxd5
Ba6 $44 {offers Black excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 9... g6 (9... Kf8
{[%csl Rf8][%cal Ye1g1] has been played here as well, but I imagine that when
White will just continue developing in a normal way Black can never really
equalize fully.}) 10. Bh6 Nb6 (10... Bf8 {can be met by} 11. Bxf8 Kxf8 12. Qd4
$16 {[%csl Rd5] and Black has some serious issues.}) 11. Bb3 (11. Bd3 {is also
possible.}) 11... d5 12. Qg3 Bf5 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ye1g1] and White has just
a more pleasant position in Warmerdam-Ernst, Vlissingen 2017, although it
should be said that Black is quite solid too.} *

