Nf3 {has been played by some 2700+ player, but so far the results haven't been
impressive.}) 5... Qg6 (5... Bb4+ $6 6. c3 Be7 (6... Bd6 $16 {is better,
though it doesn't make much sense as White hasn't weakened his kingside yet
with the move f2-f3.}) 7. Bd3 Ne5 8. O-O Nxd3 9. Qxd3 {and White's position is
very easy to play, as Black has some issues solving his coordination problems
on the kingside e.g.} Qd6 10. Qe2 a5 11. Na3 Qg6 12. Nb5 Bd8 13. Bf4 d6 14. Qc4
Qg4 15. Bxd6 $18 {with a crushing attack for White in Rublevsky-Aleksandrov,
Budva 2004.}) (5... Nge7 6. Nc3 $16) 6. f3 $1 (6. Nc3 Bb4 {is comfortable for
Black.}) (6. Qe2 $6 {is a bit strange, since after} Nf6 {White plays} 7. f3 {
anyway.} (7. e5 Nd5 {is quite nice for Black.}) 7... a5 $1 ({Much stronger than
} 7... Bb4+ $6 8. c3 Be7 9. c4 (9. Bf4 $2 {fails to} d5 $1 10. e5 Nh5 $19 {
and White was already in big trouble in Mousavi-Safarli, Nakhchivan 2018.})
9... O-O 10. Nc3 Re8 11. Be3 Bb4 {and now in Laveryd-Hector, Sweden 1998,
White should have played} 12. Qd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Ya2a3,Ye1c1]}) 8. Be3 (8. a4
Bb4+ 9. c3 Be7 {with excellent play for Black as in Tovio-De la Ossa,
Dosquebradas 2018. White's knight can't be developed to c3, while} 10. c4 $2 {
is not very attractive as Black installs a piece on b4.} Nb4 $17) 8... d5 $1 9.
Nc3 (9. exd5 Nxd5 {is just great for Black.}) 9... dxe4 10. O-O-O ({Perhaps
better is} 10. Nb5 {though after} Bd6 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Nxd6 a4 $1 {Black
seizes the initiative.}) 10... Be7 11. Nb5 O-O 12. Nxc7 Rb8 13. Qb5 {was
played in Nakamura-Howell, Caleta 2018 and here Black could have obtained
already a decisive advantage by means of} Rd8 $1 {e.g.} 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Nd5
Nxd5 16. Qxd5 exf3 17. gxf3 Qxc2+ $1 18. Kxc2 Nb4+ {and Black wins.}) 6... Nf6
({The main alternative is} 6... Bd6 {which, in fact, has been tried in more
games.} 7. Nc3 ({Special attention needs to be paid the ultra aggressive} 7. g4
$5 {which has been employed with excellent results by Nepomniachtchi.} h5 ({
A passive move like} 7... h6 $6 {offers White exactly the type of position
he's looking for:} 8. Nc3 a6 $2 9. Be3 Nge7 10. Qe2 Qf6 11. O-O-O {and in
Nepomniachtchi-Inarkiev, Sochi blitz 2014, White developed a massive attack on
the kingside.}) 8. g5 f6 ({More challenging than} 8... Nge7 9. Nc3 Be5 10. Be3
