and even though White went on to win in Nepomniachtchi-Cheparinov, St
Petersburg 2018, his position was quite suspicious at this stage.}) 7... Nge7 (
7... Bxh2 $2 {is very tempting, but fails to} 8. Rxh2 Qg3+ 9. Ke2 $1 Qxh2 10.
Nd5 $1 {and White is winning, e.g.} Qd6 11. Bf4 Ne5 12. Nd4 $1 c6 13. Nf5 Qb8
14. Qd4 f6 15. Nxg7+ Kf7 16. Nxf6 d6 17. Nfe8 Ke7 18. Bg5+ Kd7 19. Qxe5 {
1-0 Tukhaev-Maiorov, Voronezh 2015.}) (7... Nf6 $6 {can be answered with} 8. g4
$5 {and now challenging White's early expansion with} h5 {doesn't make sense,
as after} 9. g5 {the knight is kicked back.}) 8. g3 (8. Be3 $2 Bxh2 $1 {
now the trick works as with the inclusion of 7...Nge7 Black covers the d5
square, preventing Nd5 & Bf4.} 9. Qd2 (9. Ne2 Bg3+ 10. Nxg3 Qxg3+ 11. Bf2 Qe5
12. c3 d5 $17 {and Black is just a pawn up in Khatanbaatar-Fressinet, Tromsoe
2014.}) 9... Bg3+ 10. Bf2 b6 11. O-O-O Bxf2 12. Qxf2 Bb7 13. Bd3 O-O-O {
and Black is just a healthy pawn up in Yu Yangyi-Carlsen, Dubai rapid 2014.})
8... Be5 (8... O-O 9. Bg2 f5 10. f4 Bb4 11. O-O (11. e5 d6 $132 {[%cal Yf8d8]
with counterplay for Black in Cornette, D-Enchev, Rochefort 2017.}) 11... Bxc3
12. exf5 Nxf5 13. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2][%cal Yc3c4,Yc1b2] and I believe
that White's pair of bishops is more relevant than the structural weaknesses
