14... Nxc2 15. Bg5+ Qxg5 16. Qxc2 Bf5 17. Qf2 $14 {[%csl Rd8] and since the
black king is on d8 I would take White here.}) (6... Bb4+ $6 {can best be
answered with} 7. Bd2 $1 (7. c3 $6 Bd6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb1c3] and the
provocation of the move c2-c3 helps Black.}) 7... a5 (7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 d6 9.
Nc3 Be6 {and now in Sethuraman-Sundararajan, Caleta 2017 White should just
follow his standard plan with} 10. O-O-O {[%cal Yf1b5,Yb3d4,Yg2g4,Yh2h4] when
the queen on g6 doesn't seem particularly useful.}) 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. Nb5 Bxd2+
10. Qxd2 Kd8 11. O-O-O {and there isn't anything which speaks in Black's favor:
} d6 12. Kb1 Rf8 13. g4 Qf6 14. g5 Qxf3 15. Bg2 Qg4 16. e5 Nxe5 17. Nxd6 cxd6
18. Qxd6+ Nd7 19. Rhe1 Qxg5 20. Nc5 {1-0 Nepomniachtchi-Ivanchuk, Beijing 2013.
}) 7. Bf4 $1 {The critical continuation.} (7. Nc3 {allows} Bb4 $1 8. Bd2 (8. a3
$2 {(why to force Black to take on c3?)} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Kf2 Ne5 11. Be2
{was seen in Le Roux-Loiseau, Saint-Quentin 2014 and now} b6 {[%cal Yd7d6,
Yc8b7,Yd6d5,Yf8e8,Ya8d8] offers Black excellent play.}) 8... O-O 9. Qe2 $2 {
was played in Cheparinov-Marholev, Kozloduy 2014 and here Black missed a
