9. Bb5+ Bd7 (9... c6 {is worth examining, though after} 10. Qe2+ Be7 11. d6 O-O
12. dxe7 Re8 13. Bd3 Bf5 14. Bd6 {[%csl Ge7] the pawn on e7 is a nuisance.})
10. Qe2+ Kd8 (10... Be7 {is met by} 11. d6 $1 cxd6 12. O-O $16 {[%csl Rd6]})
11. O-O Nfxd5 12. Bxd7 Kxd7 13. Rd1 Re8 14. Qd2 $1 {and White is better, but
not} (14. Qf2 $2 Kc8 15. Qxa7 {and now in Muzychuk,A-Stefanova, Baku 2016 both
players overlooked the powerful} Qa6 $1 $19 {[%csl Rc2,Rf4]})) (7... d6 $2 {
is just very passive, e.g.} 8. Nc3 Be6 9. Qd2 O-O-O 10. O-O-O d5 11. Bb5 {
with an excellent game for White in Schippers-Beerdsen, Netherlands 2017. In
case of} dxe4 12. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Ra7] Black is in trouble.}) 8. Kf2 $1 ({
In case of} 8. c3 $6 Be7 9. Qd2 O-O $1 {White has more difficulties developing
the queenside, but not} (9... d6 $6 {as played in Tagelsir-Saeed, Sharjah 2018
allows} 10. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ya3b5]})) 8... O-O ({Another critical line, which
deserves further investigation, goes} 8... a5 $5 9. Bd3 ({I rather refrain from
} 9. a3 $6 Be7 $1) ({Possible is} 9. a4 {but then} d5 $5 10. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl
Rf2] potentially leads to sharp play.}) 9... Nh5 10. Bxc7 a4 11. c3 Be7 12. Nd4
Bc5 13. e5 Qh6 {and now White can simplify the position with 14.Bd6 or perhaps
