{[%evp 0,10,19,28,28,25,21,25,25,23,28,-7,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4
4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+ ({In case Black wants to refrain from the main lines
with 5...Bb6, before retreating the bishop to e7 with it makes sense inserting
this check. After} 5... Be7 {White has the additional option developing with}
6. Nc3 {when it turns out Black's position is very solid, though somewhat
passive as well.}) (5... Bb6 {will be discussed in Chapters 6-9.}) 6. c3 ({
In my opinion, the most principled continuation, though alternatives are worth
examining too.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bd3 d5 {has featured some GM games but often
leads to simplified positions. White may have some temporal initiative though.}
) ({It seems to me that after} 6. Bd2 a5 $1 {Black is in reasonable shape as
long as he refrains from capturing on d2 too quickly.} ({After} 6... Bxd2+ $2
7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O-O {[%cal Yf2f3,Yg2g4] White has a very pleasant
advantage.}) 7. a3 Be7 $1 {[%cal Yg8f6,Ya5a4,Yd7d5] and White's results
haven't been impressive. Black's has quite some dynamical possibilities in the
centre and the fact that White needs to reckon with ...a5-a4 is quite
unpleasant from a practical point of view as well.} (7... Bxd2+ $6 8. Qxd2 Nf6
(8... a4 $2 9. Nd4 Qf6 10. Nb5 $1 (10. c3 $2 {was seen in Tari-Duda, Doha 2014,
but is unproblematic for Black.}) 10... Qxb2 11. Qc3 Qxc3+ {and a draw was
agreed in Keetman-Warmerdam, Maastricht 2017, though after} 12. N1xc3 Kd8 13.
Nd5 $16 {Black is in huge trouble.}) 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O-O {gives White
comfortable play, as has been seen in many games, including Ni Hua-Eljanov,
Saratov 2011.}) (7... Bd6 $2 {[%csl Rd6]} 8. Nc3 (8. Be3 $6 Nf6 9. Nc3 {
was seen in Nepomniachtchi-Mamedyarov, Beijing 2014 and here} Be5 $132 {
[%cal Ye8g8,Yd7d5] should give Black reasonable play.}) 8... Nf6 (8... Be5 $6
9. f4 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Nf6 11. Qf3 {is fantastic for White.}) 9. f4 $1 O-O 10. Be3
$1 (10. Qf3 $2 {runs into} a4 $1 11. Nc1 Nd4 $1 12. Qd3 Bc5 $19 {[%csl Rc1,Re1]
[%cal Yd7d5] and Black is taking over.}) 10... Re8 11. Qf3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rd6,
Ge4,Gf4][%cal Yf1d3] followed by Bd3 when White is controlling the centre,
while Black is struggling to get his pieces out.})) 6... Be7 7. Bf4 ({I like
this simple developing move. The main alternative here is} 7. f4 {but then
after} d6 {[%cal Yg8h6,Yf7f5,Ye8g8] Black will likely proceed with ...Nh6, an
idea from opening expert Romanishin. In the ensuing positions, I prefer White
too, but Black isn't without counterplay.}) 7... d6 (7... Bg5 8. Bg3 {[%csl
Rg5]} (8. Qd2 {The exchange off dark-squared bishops after} Bxf4 9. Qxf4 Nf6
$11 {worked out well for Black in Matsuura-Romanishin, Rio de Janeiro 2018.})
8... d6 (8... Nh6 {looks a bit strange now, e.g.} 9. N1d2 O-O 10. Bc4 d6 11.
O-O Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 {and now in Fressinet-Le Roux, Haguenau 2013 White could
have obtained a pleasant edge with} 13. f4 Bh4 14. Qe1 Bxg3 15. Qxg3 $14 {
[%cal Ya1e1]}) 9. Bd3 h5 {was seen in Arzumanian-Romanishin, Kharkov 2007 and
here I would recommend White to proceed with} (9... Ne5 {was played in
Steel-Ivanchuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011 and I would like to suggest to improve
White's play with} 10. Bb5+ (10. Be2 $6 Ng6 $1 $132) 10... c6 11. Be2 $14 {
[%cal Yf2f4]}) 10. h4 $14 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Yb1d2,Yb3d4] with a more pleasant
position.}) 8. N1d2 (8. Be2 {has been played here as well and transposes to
the Main Line after} Nf6 9. N1d2) 8... Nf6 9. Be2 ({Simple and effective, not
allowing ...Bg4 anytime soon. In a couple of games, White has opted for} 9. Bd3
{and also obtained more pleasant positions, e.g.} Bg4 (9... Ne5 10. Be2 O-O 11.
O-O b6 $14 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yd1c2,Ya1e1,Yf4g3,Yf2f4] was seen in
Solodovnichenko-Georgiev, La Massana 2012, but since White has a very simple
plan completing his development and bring up the f-pawn, I'm not a big fan of
having the knight on e5.}) 10. Be2 Qd7 11. h3 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8
14. Rfe1 Bf8 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Ge4] Wang Hao-Noe, Karlsruhe 2018.}) 9... O-O 10.
O-O Re8 11. Qc2 ({In the following game Black decided to fianchetto his
dark-squared bishop with} 11. Re1 Bf8 12. Qc2 g6 13. Rad1 Bg7 14. h3 Qe7 {
[%csl Ge4][%cal Yf4h2,Ye2f1,Yb3c1,Yc1d3] and now in Solodovnichenko-Petrosian,
Albena 2013, rather than bringing the knight from b3 to f3, I would like to
see White playing moves like Bf1, Bh2 and the knight manoeuvre Nc1-d3, like in
the Main Line.}) 11... Bf8 ({Even in case Black succeeds in trading off the
light-squared bishops his lack of space remains unpleasant.} 11... Bg4 12. Bxg4
Nxg4 13. h3 Nf6 14. Rad1 Bf8 15. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Ge4]} Ne5 16. Bh2 c6 {
Perhaps Black should refrain from playing this move, but what to do instead?}
17. f4 Ned7 18. Kh1 Qc7 19. Nf3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4]} d5 20. e5 Ne4 21. c4 Qb6 22.
Bg1 Qb4 23. Nbd2 Nxd2 24. Rxd2 Nb6 25. Bxb6 axb6 26. cxd5 Qxf4 27. d6 {and
White has a decisive advantage in Popov-Dzhumaev, Kolkata 2013.}) 12. Rad1 Ne5
(12... Bg4 {leads to similar play as after 11...Bg4.}) 13. Bg3 Bd7 14. h3 c6
15. f4 Ng6 16. Bf3 Qc7 17. Nc1 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Gd3][%cal Yb3c1,Yc1d3] A nice
maneuver worth remembering!} Rad8 18. Rfe1 Kh8 {A clear sign Black is lacking
an active plan.} 19. Nd3 d5 20. e5 Ng8 21. c4 $16 {[%csl Ge5] and White is
clearly better in Korobov-Nyback, Legnica 2013.} *

