{[%evp 0,19,18,34,34,21,24,10,9,9,33,9,-7,-7,-7,-29,-36,-47,-45,-66,-35,-50]} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 a5 {
This move got into fashion when Vachier-Lagrave played it against Carlsen back
in 2014.} 8. e5 ({The principled continuation, leading to incredibly sharp
play. However, since I have failed to prove anything for White here I would
just recommend} 8. a4 O-O (8... Nb4 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 d6 11. O-O-O Qe7 12. f3
Bd7 13. Kb1 {and it turns out Black's position is actually quite unpleasant as
it's difficult to decide what to do with the king.} g5 (13... O-O 14. g4 $1 $36
) 14. Bf2 Bxf2 15. Qxf2 Be6 16. Nd4 $16 {[%cal Yh2h4,Yc3b5] and Black is in
big trouble in Volokitin-Eljanov, Kiev 2013.}) 9. Bg5 (9. Be3 d5 $1 {looks
fine for Black, e.g.} 10. Bxb6 cxb6 11. O-O-O Nb4 12. Qd2 (12. e5 Re8 $132)
12... Be6 13. e5 Ne4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd4 $2 (15. Qxd8 {should still be about
equal.}) 15... Qd5 $1 16. b3 Qxe5 $19 {and Black is winning in
Beerdsen-Vrolijk, Wijk aan Zee 2018.}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 {when play transposes
to positions discussed in Chapter 9.}) 8... O-O 9. exf6 a4 10. Nd5 {The
alternatives are only leading to problems for White.} (10. fxg7 $2 Re8 11. Be3
axb3 12. cxb3 Nd4 13. Qh5 Ra5 $1 {and Black is in excellent shape, e.g.} 14.
Nb5 (14. Nd5 Nc2+ 15. Kd2 Nb4 16. Bc4 {and now in Draganic-Nikcevic, Bijelo
Polje 2016 Black should have played} Nxd5 $1 17. Bxd5 Qf6 {with a decisive
advantage for Black.}) 14... Rxe3+ 15. fxe3 Qe7 16. O-O-O Nxb5 17. Bd3 Bxe3+
18. Rd2 (18. Kb1 {fails to} Na3+) 18... h6 19. Qf5 Bxd2+ 20. Kxd2 Qg5+ 21. Qxg5
hxg5 22. Bxb5 Rxb5 23. Re1 Kxg7 24. Re8 Ra5 25. Rxc8 Rxa2 {with a winning rook
endgame for Black:} 26. g4 (26. Rxc7 Rxb2+ 27. Kc3 Rxg2 28. Rxb7 g4 29. Rxd7
Rxh2 30. b4 g3 31. Rd1 Kh6 32. Rg1 Rh3 33. Kd4 Kg5 {0-1 Senzacqua-Carrettoni,
ICCF email 2015.}) (26. Kc2 {runs into} Ra6 $1 27. Rxc7 Rc6+ 28. Rxc6 bxc6 $19)
26... Rxb2+ 27. Kc3 Rxh2 28. Rxc7 Rh3+ 29. Kc2 Rg3 30. Rxb7 Rxg4 31. Rxd7 Rb4
$19 {Senzacqua-Carrettoni, ICCF email 2014.}) (10. Qg4 $2 Qxf6 11. Nd2 d5 $1 (
11... Qxf2+ $2 {enables White to consolidate with} 12. Kd1 d5 13. Qg3 Qd4 14.
Bd3 Bg4+ 15. Nf3 a3 16. Rb1 $16 {Tsydypov-Bakunts, Moscow 2017.}) 12. Qg3 Re8+
13. Be2 Nd4 14. Kd1 Nxe2 15. Nxe2 Bf5 $36 {and Black retains a powerful
initiative and a pawn for the piece. White has difficulties completing his
development.}) (10. Nd2 $2 Re8 11. Nde4 d5 {and Black regains the piece while
retaining fantastic piece play. Oleksienko-Tari, Gjakova 2016.}) 10... Re8 ({
An important zwischenzug. Inferior is} 10... axb3 {when White has the
additional option of} 11. Ne7+ $1 (11. Qg4 g6 12. Bc4 Re8+ 13. Be3 {transposes
to the Main Line.}) 11... Kh8 12. Bg5 g6 {and now White has quite a number of
promising continuations, of which} (12... Rxa2 {runs into} 13. fxg7+ Kxg7 14.
Qh5 $1 Qxe7+ 15. Bxe7 Rxa1+ 16. Kd2 Nxe7 17. Qe5+ Kg8 18. Qxe7 $18) 13. Qe4 $1
{with the idea of 14.Qh4 looks the most dangerous.}) 11. Be3 axb3 12. Qg4 g6
13. Bc4 (13. Be2 $6 {was played in Stevanic-Matviishen, Porto Carras 2018 and
now Black should consider} Bxe3 14. fxe3 Re5 {with absolute control.}) 13...
Nb4 ({A nice idea to simplify matters. Also possible is} 13... Bd4 14. Bxb3
Bxb2 15. O-O Bxf6 16. Rae1 d6 {and Black is OK in Tari-Torre, Baku 2016.}) 14.
Nxb4 (14. Qg5 $2 Nxd5 (14... Nxc2+ 15. Kd2 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Ra5 $1 {favors Black.}
) 15. Bxd5 bxc2 16. O-O d6 17. Bxb6 cxb6 {[%cal Ye8e5]} 18. f4 Bf5 19. g4 Ra5
$1 {and Black is winning in Darini-Mchedlishvili, Guilan 2016.}) 14... d5 15.
Qf4 dxc4 16. O-O bxc2 17. Nd5 (17. Bxb6 cxb6 18. Nd5 Re6 (18... Qxd5 $2 19. Qh6
$18) 19. Qxc4 Kh8 (19... Rd6 20. Ne7+ Kf8 21. Qh4 Ke8 22. Qe4 Kf8 23. Qxc2 {
and a draw was agreed in Lakatos-Kishkin, ICCF email 2015.} Rxf6 24. Nxc8 Rxc8
$11) 20. Qxc2 Rd6 (20... Qxd5 $2 21. Rad1 Qe5 22. Rd8+ Re8 23. Qc7 $1) 21. Ne3
Qxf6 22. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Be6 {and soon a draw had been agreed in
Saric-Malakhov, Zagreb 2018.}) 17... Re6 18. Qxc4 Bxe3 19. fxe3 b5 20. Qc5 Bb7
(20... Qd6 21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Qxd6 Rxd6 23. Nxc8 Rxc8 24. Rac1 Rd2 {½-½
Senturk-Hoeppenstein, ICCF email 2016.}) 21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Qxc2 Raa6 23. Rac1 $6
(23. Rad1 $11) 23... Rxf6 24. Rxf6 Rxf6 25. Qxc7 Qd3 $5 (25... Qd2 {led to a
draw by force after} 26. Qb8+ Kg7 27. Qg8+ Kh6 28. Qf8+ Kh5 29. Rc5+ g5 30.
Rxg5+ Kxg5 (30... Kh4 31. g3+) 31. Qg7+ Rg6 32. Qe5+ f5 33. h4+ Kh5 34. Qxf5+
Kh6 35. Qf8+ Kh5 36. Qf5+ Kh6 37. Qf8+ Kh5 38. Qf5+ {½-½ Vachier
Lagrave-Carlsen, Saint Louis 2014.}) 26. Qc3 (26. Qb8+ {fails after} Kg7 27.
Qg8+ Kh6 28. Qf8+ Kh5 29. Rc5+ g5 30. Rxg5+ Kh4 $3 31. g3+ Kxg5 32. Qg7+ Rg6
33. Qe5+ f5 $19) 26... Qxc3 27. Rxc3 Rd6 $15 *

