{[%evp 0,129,21,14,20,20,20,14,14,14,6,3,7,-15,1,-37,-37,-39,16,-3,15,-11,15,
20,24,23,9,3,8,1,10,16,12,2,2,16,19,23,23,24,31,24,47,28,50,32,47,40,28,20,46,
29,36,27,27,35,25,31,22,1,15,14,52,52,50,49,0,-18,-13,-6,0,-90,-92,-166,-126,
-166,-166,-135,-159,-159,-159,-185,-173,-277,-193,-193,-197,-211,-254,-160,
-160,-160,-76,-76,-76,-76,-76,-76,-84,-41,-41,0,140,181,-159,418,418,484,484,
478,550,582,595,538,613,633,697,754,828,1120,1268,1236,1587,2023,1315,1881,
2267,2522,1847,29976,29977,2244]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5.
Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 O-O (7... a5 {see previous chapter.}) 8. Bg5 Nd4 ({
The main continuation is} 8... h6 9. Bh4 {which has been examined in the next
chapter.}) ({It's now too late for} 8... a5 $2 {in view of} 9. Nd5 $1 {and
Black's kingside will be weakened.}) 9. Qd2 $1 ({Nothing can be gained from} 9.
Nxd4 Bxd4 10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Re8 ({There is no reason for Black to play} 
11... d6 $6 {in view of} 12. e5 Re8 13. Qe3 $1 $36) 12. e5 (12. Qf3 d6 {
is unproblematic for Black as he doesn't have to fear the doubled f-pawns when
queens are exchanged.}) 12... Qe7 ({Also possible is} 12... d5 $5 13. Rd3 Qe7 {
and Black seems to be faring well in the ensuing complications, but not} (13...
Bg4 $2 14. Qe3 Bf5 15. Qf4 $1 {and White is winning in Yu-Zhang, China 2017.}))
13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qg4+ Kf8 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Qd4 Qxd4 17. cxd4 d6 18. Bd3 h6 {
and Black is OK in Duda-Hracek, Poland 2013.}) (9. Qd3 $2 {fails to} Nxb3 10.
cxb3 Bxf2+ $1 $19 {and White was already lost in Nepomniachtchi-Le Quang Liem,
Beijing blitz 2013.}) 9... Nxb3 10. axb3 {A critical moment as Black has some
issues to solve. First of all, the knight on f6 is pinned and that's quite
unpleasant for Black completing his development. Secondly, White has a
pleasant space advantage and hence Black should try to generate counterplay
against the pawn on e4, by playing Re8 or launch a quick ...d7-d5.} h6 ({
The alternative is} 10... Re8 11. O-O-O $1 (11. f3 $6 {is less precise,
because of} h6 $1 12. Be3 (12. Bf4 $6 d5 $1 13. O-O-O d4 {with comfortable
play for Black in Svidler-Ponomariov, Tashkent 2012.}) (12. Bh4 $2 {runs into}
Nxe4 $1) 12... Bxe3 13. Qxe3 d5 $1 $11 {with a transposition to the line 12...
Re8 13.f3?!}) 11... h6 12. h4 $5 {The critical way, exploiting this specific
move-order. By maintaining the bishop on g5 Black has the unpleasant decision
to make whether capturing the bishop or not. Objectively Black should be able
to neutralize White's aggressive setup, but an unprepared player doesn't want
to face this OTB!} (12. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 13. f4 (13. Nd5 Qd8 {is leading nowhere.})
13... d6 14. Kb1 Ba5 15. Bd3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 a5 {and White's king was more
vulnerable in Lorenzo de la Riva-Baryshpolets, Badalona 2011.}) 12... c6 (12...
d6 13. f3 (13. Bc4 Be6 14. Bxe6 (14. Qf4 $5 {[%cal Yd1d3] might pose more
practical problems.}) 14... Rxe6 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. f4 Rg6 17. Qe2 Rg3 $132 {
and Black was hanging in there in Darini-Sargissian, Dubai 2013.}) 13... hxg5
14. hxg5 Nh7 15. f4 Nxg5 16. Bc4 (16. fxg5 Re5 $1 17. g6 Be6 $1 {and Black is
doing reasonably well, but not} (17... fxg6 $2 18. Bc4+ Be6 19. Bxe6+ Rxe6 20.
Qd5 Qe7 21. Qxb7 $16 {which clearly favors White.})) 16... Nxe4 ({An
improvement upon} 16... Be6 $2 17. fxg5 Bxc4 18. bxc4 c6 19. Qf4 Qd7 {and now
in Cheparinov-Melkumyan, Yerevan 2014 White forgot to finish off the game. The
simplest way is} 20. Qh4 Kf8 21. e5 $1 Rxe5 22. Qh8+ {and White picks up the
rook.}) 17. Nxe4 Rxe4 18. Qd5 Rxf4 19. Qh5 Kf8 20. Rde1 Be6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22.
Rxe6 (22. Qe2 {and now with either 22...Qf6 or 22...Rf6 Black can return some
material, retaining control over the position.}) 22... Bf2 23. g4 Qd7 24. Qg5
Qxe6 25. Rh8+ Kf7 26. Qxf4+ Ke7 27. Qg5+ Kf7 28. Qf4+ $11 {and a repetition is
inevitable, as} (28. Rxa8 $2 {fails to} Qe1#)) ({Opening the h-file with} 12...
hxg5 $2 {is asking for problems:} 13. hxg5 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Bd3 Re5 16.
Bh7+ $1 Kf8 17. Bf5 $1 Kg8 18. Rh3 $18 {followed by 19. Rdh1.}) 13. Bc4 (13.
Kb1 $5 $146 {could be an interesting new idea worth examining.}) 13... Bc7 (
13... d6 14. f3 $2 d5 $1 {as played in Barbosa-Quesada Perez, Buenos Aires
2015 is exactly what Black was hoping for. The point is that after} 15. exd5
hxg5 {White can't recapture on g5, as} 16. hxg5 {runs into} Be3 $19) (13... d5
14. exd5 hxg5 15. hxg5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Nxd5 Be6 18. Nf6+ (18. Qf4 {
only leads to a draw after} Bxd5 19. Qh4 Kf8 20. Qb4+ Kg8 21. Qh4 $11) 18...
gxf6 19. Qc3 Qxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Rad8 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Qxf6 {[%cal Yg5g6] and
White is better here, though with precise play it seems to me that Black
should be able to hold.}) 14. f4 ({More challenging is} 14. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 15.
Qxh6 {with a possible repetition.}) 14... d5 15. exd5 hxg5 $2 (15... b5 $1 {
had to be tried, when Black seems to be in reasonable shape.}) 16. hxg5 Bg4 {
was seen in Drori-Pashikian, Batumi 2018 and now} 17. gxf6 Bxd1 18. fxg7 Qf6
19. Qxd1 $18 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Yd1h5] with a decisive advantage for White.}) 11.
Be3 $1 (11. Bh4 $2 {allows} Nxe4) (11. Bf4 $6 Re8 12. O-O-O (12. f3 d5 {
with easy play for Black.}) 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Bd3 Re6 15. Bc4 Rf6 $1
16. Bg3 (16. g4 $6 {is strongly met by} d5 $1 17. g5 Rxf4 $1 18. Qxf4 hxg5 19.
Qf3 c6 $17 {and Black is clearly better in Tate-Howell, Douglas 2014.}) 16...
c6 17. Be5 d5 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 {and Black has reasonable compensation for the
exchange in Sengupta-L'Ami, Dieren 2013, as he is likely to win a second pawn
on f2.}) 11... Bxe3 ({Prior to our game, Howell had tried to solve Black's
problems with the aid of a pawn sacrifice, though after} 11... c6 $6 12. Bxb6
Qxb6 13. O-O-O Re8 14. f3 d5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 Be6 {my
intended improvement was} 18. Qb5 (18. Qd4 Qc7 19. Qc3 Qe7 20. Bd3 (20. Kb1 $5)
20... Rac8 21. Qd4 Bxb3 $11 {with equality in Tari-Howell, Tbilisi 2017.})
18... Qf2 19. Bd3 Qxg2 20. Be4 $16 {[%csl Ge4] and although the position
remains complex, I am sure that White is better.}) (11... Re8 $2 12. Bxb6 cxb6
{looks ugly and is quite bad, because after} 13. f3 {Black can't play} d5 14.
O-O-O {and White wins a pawn.}) 12. Qxe3 d5 (12... Re8 13. O-O-O $1 (13. f3 $6
{allows Black to play} d5 $1 14. O-O-O c6 15. Qd4 (15. Qc5 Qb6 16. Qxb6 axb6
17. exd5 Ra1+ 18. Kd2 Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 Rd8 $11 {and soon in both games Bruzon
Batista-Fressinet & Wang Hao-Aronian from the Olympiad in Istanbul 2012 the
players agreed to a draw.}) 15... Be6 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Bxd5
$11 {with equality in Nakamura-Dominguez, Bilbao 2014.}) 13... c6 14. Qd4 $1 {
A key idea, as White prevents Black from playing the liberating move ...d7-d5
and therefore fails to equalize.} Qe7 (14... Qa5 15. Kb1 (15. Bd3 $5) 15... d5
16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 cxd5 19. Bb5 $14 {and Black had a very
unpleasant task in Volokitin-Roiz, Israel 2013, but not} (19. Rxd5 $2 Re1+ 20.
Ka2 Bg4 $15)) 15. f3 b5 16. Qd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Re7 (17... Re6 18. Rxe6 dxe6 19.
e5 Nd5 20. Ne4 {[%csl Rb5,Rc6,Rc8][%cal Yc2c4] and Black's under serious
pressure in Negi-Sargissian, Leon 2012.}) 18. g4 Ne8 19. Rd2 d6 20. h4 $14 {
and White has a very pleasant space advantage in Babujian-Harutyunian, Yerevan
2014.}) 13. O-O-O c6 (13... Ng4 {was seen in Darini-Bruzon Batista, Istanbul
2012 and I think that White can best play now} 14. Qf4 $1 d4 15. Nb5 c5 16. Be2
{and White is slightly better, e.g.} Qg5 17. Qxg5 hxg5 18. Rdf1 $36 {[%csl Rg4]
[%cal Yb5c7,Yb5d6,Yh2h4,Yf2f3] and Black remains under pressure.}) (13... Be6
14. e5 $36 {followed by 15.f4}) 14. exd5 Nxd5 ({Trading off one pair of
knights helps Black developing some counterplay on the queenside. Inferior is} 
14... cxd5 $6 15. Qd4 Qa5 (15... Be6 16. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yf2f3,Yg2g4,
Yh2h4]}) 16. Kb1 Bf5 17. f3 $1 (17. Nxd5 $2 Rad8) 17... Rfd8 18. g4 Bh7 19. h4
{and since White is about to open the files on the kingside, Black is pretty
forced to exchange queens and enter a technically lost ending. Amin went on to
convert his advantage in exemplary style:} Qb6 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rd4 Ra5 22. b4
Ra7 23. b3 Rda8 24. Kb2 Ra1 25. Bg2 Rxh1 26. Bxh1 g5 27. hxg5 hxg5 28. Nxd5
Nxd5 29. Rxd5 f6 30. Bg2 Bxc2 31. Bf1 Bg6 32. Bc4 Kg7 33. Rd7+ Kh6 34. Rxb7 Rd8
35. Rxb6 Rd2+ 36. Ka3 Kg7 37. b5 f5 38. Re6 fxg4 39. fxg4 Rd7 40. b6 {1-0
Amin-Safarli, Hoogeveen 2018.}) 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Rd4 ({Perhaps simpler is} 16.
Qd4 Bf5 17. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] and also after the exchange of Black's bad
bishop he still retains some problems in view of the weakness on d5.}) 16...
Be6 17. Bd3 Re8 18. Qd2 (18. Qf4 $5) 18... Qb6 19. g4 a5 20. h4 Bd7 21. Qf4 (
21. g5 $6 a4 $1 {is dangerous for White.}) 21... Bb5 22. Bxb5 Qxb5 23. Kb1 Rac8
(23... Re4 $5 24. Rxe4 dxe4 25. Qxe4 a4 $132 {[%csl Rb1]}) 24. Rhd1 Re2 25.
Rxd5 Rcxc2 26. Rxb5 Rxb2+ 27. Ka1 Ra2+ 28. Kb1 Reb2+ 29. Kc1 Rc2+ {½-½
Ris-Howell, Daventry 2018.} *

