{[%evp 0,19,50,30,38,38,8,8,8,8,30,-1,-3,-3,-3,-37,-35,-45,-45,-59,-23,-39]} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 O-O 8. Bg5
h6 9. Bh4 (9. Be3 $6 {makes little sense, as ...h6 is quite useful.} d5 10.
O-O-O d4 $36 {Van Foreest, J-L'Ami, Amstelveen rapid 2016.}) 9... a5 (9... Nd4
$6 10. Qd3 (10. Qd2 $2 Nxe4 $1) 10... Nxb3 11. axb3 $1 ({The most natural
recapture is better than} 11. cxb3 {which was played in the high-profile game
Le Quang Liem-Fedoseev, Danzhou 2018. Here I would recommend Black to continue
with} c6 12. O-O-O d5 {with similar play as in the Main Line, without the
inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and a7-a5. I guess that excluding those moves
helps Black, as in some lines the bishop on b6 would be hanging and the white
king likes to hide on a2 if possible.} 13. e5 $2 {was played in Moore-Korneev,
Hastings 2018 and here should have played} g5 14. Bg3 Ng4 $15 {[%csl Gb7,Gc6,
Gd5,Re5][%cal Yf8e8]}) 11... Re8 (11... d6 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Be2 c6 {was seen
in Salgado Lopez-Erenberg, Minsk 2017 and here White should have gone for} 14.
f4 {[%cal Ye2f3,Yh1e1]}) 12. O-O-O c6 13. f3 (13. f4 $2 d5 14. e5 g5 $1 $132 {
works out well for Black.}) 13... Qe7 14. Kb1 Bc7 (14... d5 $2 15. exd5 Rd8 16.
d6 {and White is just a healthy pawn up in Sargsyan-Afanasiev, chess.com 2019.}
) 15. Bg3 $1 {and since Black failed to push his d-pawn at a proper moment,
White is just better.}) (9... Re8 10. O-O-O d6 11. f3 Be6 12. Kb1 Qe7 (12... a5
{was seen in Ivanchuk-Morozevich, Morelia/Linares 2007 and now White's
simplest reply is} 13. a4 $1 $36 {[%cal Yg2g4]}) 13. g4 Rad8 (13... a5 14. a4
Rad8 (14... Bxb3 15. cxb3 Qe6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd5 {and White's position
plays itself. The following game shows how quickly White builds up an attack:}
Qd8 18. h4 Nd4 19. Qg2 c6 20. Nxb6 Qxb6 21. g5 Ne6 22. Bc4 d5 23. exd5 cxd5 24.
Bb5 Re7 25. gxh6 g6 26. h5 Kh7 27. Qg3 Nc5 28. Rxd5 Rd8 29. hxg6+ fxg6 30. Qg5
{1-0 Tukhaev-Asadli, Kocaeli 2017.}) 15. Qg2 $1 Nb4 16. Nd4 Bxd4 17. Rxd4 c5
18. Rd1 g5 {was seen in Cheparinov-Navara, Tbilisi 2017 and now rather than
retreating the bishop, which should be OK for White as well, the machine
recommends} 19. Bxg5 $1 hxg5 20. h4 $40 {and White develops a massive attack.})
14. Qe1 Ne5 15. Be2 Ng6 16. Bg3 Bxb3 17. axb3 d5 18. exd5 Ba5 19. Bc4 Qf8 20.
Qf2 {and Black didn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn in Bok-Avrukh,
Biel 2012.}) (9... d6 10. O-O-O Be6 (10... Re8 {see 9...Re8.}) 11. Kb1 Re8 12.
f3 {see 9...Re8.}) 10. a4 ({The sharp alternative} 10. O-O-O $5 {is worth
examining.} a4 11. Nd2 {though in my opinion Black's position is absolutely
fine after} Bd4 $1 (11... a3 $6 {This is the most consistent continuation, but
apparently White is obtaining a dangerous attack.} 12. e5 axb2+ 13. Kb1 Nd5 (
13... Nd4 14. Qe1 ({Less convincing is} 14. Qd3 $6 d5 $1 15. Bxf6 (15. exf6 {
is met by} Bf5) 15... gxf6 16. Qg3+ {was played in Mikes-Rubil, Austria 2019
and now Black's best the perhaps suprising move} Kh7 {not fearing} 17. Bd3+ $6
f5 $1) 14... Nd5 $2 15. Nxd5 Qxh4 16. Qe4 Qxe4 17. Nxe4 Nc6 18. Nxb6 cxb6 19.
Nd6 Nxe5 20. Bb5 $18 {with a totally dominating position for White in
Korneev-Maiorov, Voronezh 2013.}) (13... Bd4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qg4+ Kh8 16. Qh4
Kg7 17. Qg4+ Kh8 18. Qf4 Kg7 19. Nde4 Bxe5 (19... fxe5 $2 20. Qg4+ Kh7 21. Qf5+
Kg7 22. Rd3 Rh8 23. Rg3+ Kf8 24. Qg4 d5 25. Qg7+ Ke7 26. Qf6+ Kd7 27. Qxf7+ Ne7
28. Nxd5 {with a crushing attack for White in Mikes-Malinovsky, Ostrava 2018.})
20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Qh5 Kg7 {and here rather than repeating moves, White
continues with} 22. Nd5 $1 {(intending f4)} f5 23. Ng3 d6 24. f4 Bd4 25. Bc4
$36 {and Black remains under heavy pressure.}) 14. Nxd5 Qxh4 15. Ne4 d6 {
and here White has a beautiful resource:} 16. Ndf6+ $1 gxf6 17. g3 {and in
Vallejo Pons-Tkachiev, Legnica 2013 Black was forced to give up his queen for
two pieces, which didn't give him sufficient compensation.}) (11... Re8 $6 {
was seen in Sychev-Postny, Skopje 2019 and here my improvement for White is}
12. Nc4 $5 Bd4 13. Nb5 {and White seems to be faring well in the ensuing
complications.}) 12. Nb5 a3 $1 13. bxa3 (13. Nxd4 $2 Nxd4 {followed by taking
on b2 favors Black.}) (13. Nc4 Bxb2+ 14. Kb1 d6 15. Nxb2 axb2 {was simply bad
for White in Cornette-Tkachiev, Nancy 2013.}) 13... d6 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 {[%csl
Ra2,Ra3,Gd4][%cal Yc7c5] and Black is doing fine in Hoeher-Ghosh, ICCF email
2014.}) 10... Nd4 11. Qd3 (11. Nxd4 Bxd4 {is comfortable for Black in
Cerovic-Atalik, Paracin 2017.}) (11. Qd2 $2 {allows} Nxb3 12. cxb3 Nxe4 $1)
11... Nxb3 12. cxb3 c6 $1 {Black should act quickly as otherwise, he will
suffer from a lack of space.} ({Inferior is} 12... Re8 $6 13. O-O-O d6 (13...
c6 14. Qc2 g5 (14... Bc7 15. Bc4 (15. Kb1 $5) 15... Be5 {was seen in
Nikitenko-Sanal, Skopje 2019 and here I would recommend} 16. Kb1 $16 {when
White will soon launch an attack on the kingside, while Black is lacking
active counterplay.}) 15. Bg3 d5 16. f3 Be6 17. h4 $36 {and White is enjoying
his initiative in Kraus-Malinovsky, Ostrava 2018.}) 14. Qc2 Bd7 $2 ({Better is
} 14... c6 15. Bc4 Qe7 {when matters aren't that simple yet, but White's
position is definitely easier to handle.}) 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Rhe1 Qe7 17. e5 $1
dxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf8 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Re2 $16 {and Black's king is too
vulnerable in Carlsen-Bacrot, Nanjing 2010.}) (12... d6 13. O-O-O Be6 14. Qc2 (
{Immediate tactics aren't working in White's favour, e.g.} 14. e5 $2 dxe5 15.
Qf3 Bd4 16. Ne4 Bd5 17. Bd3 $2 (17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $1 {is fine for Black.}) 17...
Bxe4 18. Bxe4 {and now in Yu,R-Zhou,W China 2016 Black could have retained a
decisive advantage with} Ra6 $1 $19) 14... Qe7 15. Kb1 c6 16. Be2 g5 17. Bg3 d5
18. h4 $36 {and Black's position in Paulik-Canibal, ICCF email 2012 looks
quite suspicious.}) ({Regrouping the bishop with} 12... Bc5 13. O-O-O Be7 {
as was seen in Braeuer-Gonda, Budapest 2015 takes too much time and here I
would suggest} 14. e5 Ne8 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qe4 $16 {with ideas like Bd3 and/
or Nd5.}) (12... d5 $2 {as played in Ivekovic-Rade, Biograd na Moru 2018
should be answered with} 13. Nxd5 g5 14. Nxb6 $1 {and White remains a healthy
pawn up in all the lines.}) 13. O-O-O (13. f4 $2 {is premature, in view of} d5
$1 {and now} 14. e5 {is strongly met by} g5 $1 {and White was already lost in
Zumsande-Nyback, Finland 2016. In case of} 15. fxg5 Ng4 {his centre is falling
apart.}) 13... d5 ({The principled follow-up. After} 13... Qe7 $6 14. Kb1 Bc7 (
14... Re8 15. f3 Bc5 16. Qc2 d6 17. Bd3 Be6 18. Rhe1 {[%cal Ye4e5] with a very
pleasant advantage for White in Cvak-Kolarik, ICCF email 2016.}) 15. Qc2 ({
Less convincing is} 15. Bg3 $6 Bxg3 16. hxg3 {as played in Amin-Sunilduth Lyna,
Dubai 2017 and now} Rd8 {[%cal Yd7d5] is pretty solid for Black.}) 15... Re8
16. f3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rd7][%cal Yf1c4,Yh1e1] and Black is lacking active
counterplay.}) (13... g5 $2 14. Bg3 d5 {was played in Barseghyan-Davtyan,
Yerevan 2019, though after} 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 {Black's
compensation is insufficient.}) 14. exd5 (14. Qc2 $6 Qd6 $132 {Negi-Karpatchev,
Baden-Baden 2013.}) (14. e5 $2 {is met by} g5 $1 $17 {Puppi Lazo-Urh, Porto
Carras 2018.}) 14... cxd5 15. Bxf6 (15. Nxd5 {leads to a draw by force after}
g5 $1 ({Easier than} 15... Qxd5 16. Qxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Be6 18. Rb5 Bd8 19. Bxd8
Rc8+ $1 (19... Rfxd8 $2 20. Bc4 $1 Rdc8 21. Kc2 Bxc4 22. bxc4 Rxc4+ 23. Kb3 $16
{is very unpleasant for Black.}) 20. Bc4 Bxc4 21. bxc4 Rxc4+ 22. Kb1 Rxd8 {
was seen in Bakalchuk-Muzychuk,M Caleta 2018 and here White could have tried}
23. Rxa5 $5 {with quite a doubled-edged rook ending.}) 16. Qf3 (16. Bg3 $6 {
isn't accurate, in view of} Be6 $1 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Qb5 {and now in Wang
Hao-Malakhov, Danzhou 2017 Black should have played} Rfc8+ $5 {when the
following line seems pretty straightforward:} 19. Kb1 Qxb5 20. Bxb5 Bxb3 21.
Rd6 Ne4 22. Rxh6 Rc5 {(intending Rac8 and Nd2)} 23. Bd6 Bc2+ 24. Ka2 Rxb5 25.
axb5 Kg7 26. f3 Kxh6 27. fxe4 Bxe4 {and even though this should probably be
drawish, only Black can be better.}) 16... Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qc7+ 18. Bc4 gxh4 (
18... Be6 19. Bxg5 (19. Bg3 {could be a way for White avoiding an immediate
draw, e.g.} Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Qc6 21. Qf5 {with some compensation for the exchange,
though after} Bd4 $1 {Black seems to be in control.}) 19... Bxd5 20. Qxd5 hxg5
21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 {½-½ Nataf-Fressinet,
Drancy 2016.}) 19. Qf6 Be6 20. Rg5+ hxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Qg5+ {
½-½ Cvak-Parmet, ICCF email 2015.}) (15. Qc2 $5 d4 (15... Be6 16. Nxd5 Bxd5
17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Rxd5 Qxf2 19. Bc4 Be3+ 20. Kb1 Qxc2+ 21. Kxc2 b6 22. Rd7 Rad8
23. Bxf7+ Kh7 24. Rhd1 Rxd7 25. Rxd7 $14 {and even though Black managed to
hold this position in Cheparinov-Pashikian, Batumi 2018 I don't think many
people would enjoy defending this ending with Black. White always has ideas
with b3-b4, undoubling his b-pawns, and also a possible exchange sacrifice on
the queenside might enable the white king and queenside majority to make
further progress.}) 16. Bc4 Be6 17. Kb1 $5 ({My small refinement upon} 17. Bxe6
fxe6 18. Kb1 Qc7 19. Nb5 Qxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Ng4 21. Rhe1 Nxf2 22. Rd2 d3+ 23. Kb1 {
which was seen in Jurcik-Chovan, Slovakia 2019 and now after} Rf4 24. Bg3 Rf6 {
I don't think White has anything significant.}) 17... Rc8 (17... Bxc4 18. bxc4
$14 {[%cal Yc3d5]}) 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Qe2 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Yh4f6,Yc3e4,Yd1d3]
the position is very close to equal, but it seems to me that after taking on
f6, followed by installing a knight on e4 White obtains a nice blockade on the
light squares. A next step could be to push the pawns on the kingside, or even
consider a rook lift along the third rank.}) (15. Qf3 g5 16. Nxd5 {transposes
to 15.Nxd5.}) 15... Qxf6 16. Nxd5 Qxf2 17. Qe4 {The engine evaluates this
position as 0.00, but that means that both sides need to make a couple of
precise moves. The fact that a strong GM as Oparin goes astray indicates how
difficult it is to play this position OTB. Let's examine a couple of options.}
Kh8 $2 (17... Be6 18. Bd3 (18. Bc4 Bd8 19. Rhf1 Qh4 {looks fine for Black.})
18... g6 19. Rhf1 Qd4 (19... Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Rad8 $11) 20. Qxd4 Bxd4 21. Bc4 Be5
{and Black is fine.}) (17... Bd8 $5 {[%cal Yf2h4] A key idea, removing the
vulnerable bishop from b6, guarding some important dark squares and prepare
the retreat of the queen to h4.} 18. Bd3 g6 19. Qe5 (19. Rhf1 $6 Qh4 {is
annoying, as} 20. Qe5 $2 {runs into} Qg5+ $1) 19... Bf5 $1 (19... Bg4 20. Rdf1
Rc8+ (20... Qxg2 21. Rhg1 Qh3 22. Bc4 {looks very dangerous for Black.}) 21.
Kb1 Qc5 22. Rf4 Be6 23. Rc4 Qf2 24. Bxg6 $1 Qxg2 25. Be4 $40) (19... Be6 $2 20.
Bxg6) 20. Bxf5 Bg5+ 21. Kb1 Rae8 22. Qc3 (22. Nf6+ Bxf6 23. Qxf6 Re6 $1 $11)
22... Qxf5+ 23. Ka2 Re2 24. h4 Rc8 25. Qd4 Rcc2 26. hxg5 Qxd5 27. Qxd5 Rxb2+
28. Ka1 Ra2+ $11) 18. Rd2 Qc5+ 19. Kb1 (19. Rc2 $6 {allows} Qd4 $1) 19... Bd8
$2 (19... Be6 $2 {allows} 20. Bd3 $1 g6 21. Qe5+ Kg8 22. Bxg6 $1 {with a
crushing attack.}) ({Black's best is} 19... Bd7 {but then after} 20. Bd3 f5 21.
Qf3 Bc6 22. Bxf5 {White wins a pawn. The position is still very sharp, and
although I imagine that Black should be doing reasonably well if he brings the
rook from a8 into play, I would like to get such a position with OTB. Note that
} g6 $2 {fails to} 23. Qf4 Kh7 (23... gxf5 24. Qxh6+ Kg8 25. Rd3 $18) 24. Bxg6+
Kxg6 25. Qg3+ Kh7 26. Rc1 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5] and White wins material.} Qxd5 27.
Rxd5 Bxd5 28. Qd3+ Kg7 29. Qxd5 $18) 20. Bd3 f5 21. Qf3 Be6 {and now in
Vitiugov-Oparin, Linares 2018 White could have obtained a clear advantage by
means of} 22. Nf4 $1 Bf7 23. Bc4 $16 {after the exchange of light-squared
bishop the weaknesses in Black's position on the kingside can be felt.} *

