{[%evp 0,11,19,31,23,12,17,10,34,33,19,13,14,-2]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 (5. Nc3 {leads to the Four Knights Scotch, a very
solid line and an annoying line to face with Black when you want to play for a
win. However, it's not in the spirit with our repertoire and I prefer to enter
the Mieses Variation.}) 5... bxc6 (5... dxc6 $2 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. f3 $16 {
[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg2][%cal Yc1e3] leads to a very bad position, where White just
enjoys a clear space advantage and his 4 vs. 3 majority on the kingside.
Compared with the Berlin Defence, White's pawn is still on e4, which is an
advantage, as it takes away squares from the black minor pieces.}) 6. e5 {
The point of White's play is to exploit Black's early development of his
king's knight. Black, on the other hand, should try not to waste too much time
moving around with his knight. As a rule of thumb, we could state that in case
White manages to consolidate and strengthen his position by overprotecting the
pawn on e5 he should be doing fine. However, Black should try to challenge the
pawn weakness on e5 and try to prove White's position is overextended. In this
Chapter we briefly discuss the minor alternatives, while in the next chapters
we are focusing on our main line with 8.h4. Therefore the main line goes} (6.
Bd3 {leads to a similar type of play, in the spirit of the Scotch Four Knights,
though Black is doing very fine after the principled} d5 7. exd5 (7. e5 $6 Ng4
8. O-O Bc5 9. Bf4 g5 10. Bd2 O-O 11. Nc3 Nxe5 12. Qh5 Nxd3 13. cxd3 f6 {
was seen in Vachier Lagrave-Anand, Paris 2018, though White's compensation is
insufficient.}) 7... cxd5 {[%cal Yf8e7,Ye8g8] etc.}) (6. Qe2 {was once
successfully employed by Andreikin against Kramnik, so it could perfectly work
as a surprise weapon. The move is directed against ...d7-d5, but here my
recommendation would be} d5 $5 {anyway! The idea is} 7. exd5+ Be7 8. dxc6 O-O {
[%csl Re1,Re2][%cal Yf8e8] with excellent play for Black. Perhaps an engine
holds on for White, but practically I believe this could be very unpleasant
for White. However, in case you don't fancy the black prospects alternative
developing moves on the 6th move should be fine.}) 6... Qe7 ({The alternative} 
6... Ne4 {has been tried by fighting players like Kortschnoj, Beliavsky and
Sokolov.} 7. Qf3 (7. Qd4 f5 8. exf6 Nxf6 {[%cal Yf8e7,Ye8g8] as played in
Caruana-Sokolov, Dubai 2014 looks fine for Black.}) (7. Nd2 $5 $14) 7... Ng5 (
7... f5 8. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Re8,Rf5][%cal Yf1d3,Ye1g1] with an easy game for
White.} (8. Qxf5 $2 d5 $1 $132)) (7... Nc5 8. Bc4 Ne6 9. O-O {[%csl Ge5][%cal
Yf1e1,Yb1c3] with easy play for White.}) 8. Qg3 Ne6 (8... Ne4 9. Qe3 $1 {
[%csl Re4]}) 9. Bd3 d5 (9... d6 10. O-O dxe5 11. Qxe5 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7]}) 10.
O-O $14 {[%csl Rc6,Ge5,Gg3][%cal Yf2f5] this has been played in various games,
but in my opinion, White's edge is beyond doubt.}) (6... Nd5 7. c4 Bb4+ (7...
Nb6 8. Bd3 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 d5 10. exd6 cxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6]
Firouzja,-Bosiocic, Bandar e Anzali 2019.}) (7... Ne7 8. Bd3 Ng6 9. O-O $14) 8.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Ne7 10. Nc3 $36 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye1c1]}) 7. Qe2 Nd5 {
The main tabiya of the Mieses Variation. For many years the move} 8. c4 {
had been played almost automatically. Of course, the ensuing position are rich
and deeply analyzed. But from a practical point I don't believe it's a smart
choice, as Black has a different type of setups which White players should be
familiar with.} ({For quite some time, White players have been experimenting
with the flexible} 8. Nd2 {, not revealing the intentions with the c-pawn yet.
Evidently, there are some drawbacks to this move as well (e.g. knight can't be
developed to active square c3 and bishop on c1 temporarily blocked).}) ({
My choice for our repertoire is the perhaps somewhat the odd-looking} 8. h4 $5
{[%csl Re7,Gg5][%cal Yc1g5,Yh1h3,Yh3a3] , a move which back in 1987 had been
employed quite successfully by Scotch expert John van der Wiel. The line soon
disappeared from GM level play, until 2015 when Alexander Morozevich picked it
up and made some important contributions to the line. Recently top GMs as
Nepomniachtchi, Nakamura and Cheparinov have shown that the line is worth
further investigation. As so often with opening theory, I don't think I'm able
to prove an advantage for White in most of the lines. However, my main goal
with this repertoire is to provide the reader with an overview on the current
state of this and make you well prepared in a line you are likely to know
better than your opponents. The theory is still fresh here and I imagine a lot
of new contributions are expected to follow soon!}) *

