cxd5 $6 Nxd5 13. Bg5 f6 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. Bd2 Rb8 $15 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Yc8f5,
Yd5b4] and Black's activity more than compensates for the inferior pawn
structure in Florstedt-Kucza, Gorzow Wielkopolski 2018.}) 12... dxc4 13. g3 (
13. Nxc4 $6 Be6 $1 $132) 13... Be6 14. Bg2 Qc7 15. O-O (15. h5 $5) 15... Be7
16. Bxb6 axb6 17. Nxc4 O-O {is unproblematic for Black in Van Foreest,
J-Gledura, Brest 2018.}) (11... Bf5 $6 12. Nd2 (12. Nc3 $1 {is more active, e.
g.} Qe6 13. Qf3 Rc8 14. Be2 $14 {[%cal Yg2g4]}) 12... Qe6 13. Nf3 c5 14. Ng5 {
was played in Suarez Real-Guichard, Daventry 2018 and here Black should have
played} Qd7 $1 {not fearing the loss of a pawn, since after} 15. Bxc5+ $6 Be7
$1 $132 {White still has some difficulties completing development.}) (11... Qe6
12. Nc3 (12. Nd2 Be7 13. Nf3 Bf6 $6 ({In case of} 13... O-O {I had planned to
proceed with} 14. Qc2 {[%cal Yf1d3,Ye1c1,Yf3g5] though} Qg6 {looks OK for
Black.}) 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Qc2 {I was quite satisfied with the outcome of the
opening and it seems to me White is faster building up an initiative against
the enemies king. At least, my position is easier to handle OTB. Black went
completely astray with} g6 $2 16. h5 d5 $2 17. c5 Nd7 18. Nd4 Bxd4 19. Bxd4 a5
20. Qd2 $1 $18 {and I had a crushing attack in Ris-Hjartarson, Reykjavik 2019.}
) (12. Qc2 $2 {[%cal Yf1d3] is met by} d5 $1 {[%csl Re3]}) 12... Be7 13. O-O-O
O-O 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bf4 d5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Qf3 (17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Qxe6+ Bxe6
$14) 17... Nxf4 18. Qxf4 Qe5 {was played in Firouzja-Karthikeyan, Moscow 2019
and now White consider opting for a small endgame plus (better pawn structure)
by swapping queens.}) 12. Qc2 ({White's best try. The queen clears the way for
the bishop and also protects the pawn on b2, which makes sense as he is
intending to castle queenside. The immediate} 12. Nd2 {has been played as well,
but led in a high-profile game to a total disaster for White:} Qb7 (12... Qf6
$6 13. O-O-O d5 14. Bg5 Qd4 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nb3 Qa4 {and now in
Lintchevski-Yeritsyan, St Petersburg 2017 White should have forced the
exchange of queens by means of} 17. Qc4 $16 {with a clear advantage thanks to
a favourable pawn structure.}) (12... Qd7 $5 {looks also perfectly fine for
Black.}) 13. g3 $6 (13. Qf3 $5 {is a more sensible move.}) 13... c5 14. Rg1 Be7
15. Bg2 d5 {and Black is already in perfect shape. White's main problem is his
king which doesn't have a safe place.} 16. b4 $2 Rc8 $1 17. bxc5 Bxc5 18. cxd5
Nxd5 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Rb1 $2 Qc7 21. Ne4 Rc2 22. Qb5+ Ke7 23. Qa4 Rd8 24. Qa3+
Ke8 25. Bf3 Nc3 26. Nxc3 Rxc3 27. Qa4+ Kf8 28. Qb4+ Kg8 29. Be4 Rc4 30. Qb7 Qe5
31. f3 Qc3+ 32. Kf1 Bh3+ 33. Rg2 Qd2 {0-1 Ivanisevic-Predojevic, Mali Losinj
2017.}) 12... Qd7 (12... g6 13. Qc3 Rg8 14. Nd2 (14. Bg5 {can be nicely
answered with} Bg7 $1 15. Bxe7 Bxc3+ 16. Nxc3 Kxe7 17. b3 a5 18. Kd2 a4 {
½-½ Ivanisevic-Georgiev, K Mali Losinj 2017}) 14... Bg7 15. Qc2 {and
although probably this isn't much for White at all, I would somehow slightly
prefer his position. Probably that has to do with the fact that Black can no
longer castle kingside. An example:} Nd7 16. Nb3 (16. Be2 $14) (16. Nf3 $5)
16... f5 (16... c5 $5) 17. O-O-O Kf7 18. Nd4 Ne5 19. Be2 c5 $2 {Globus-Mindlin,
Maalot Tarshiha 2018.} 20. Bg5 $1 $18) (12... Qf6 $6 {the queen isn't well
placed here:} 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 $14 {and Black ended up in a
passive position in Perunovic-Schnider, Austria 2017} Qxb2 $2 {is asking for
trouble as after} 16. Bd4 Qb4 17. O-O $18 {White obtains a deadly initiative.})
(12... Qb7 13. Nd2 Be7 14. O-O-O d5 {was seen in Van Perlo-Steinsapir, Y ICCF
corr 1987 and now} 15. Bd4 $1 O-O 16. Bd3 h6 17. c5 {[%cal Yg2g4] seems to
pose Black some problems.}) 13. Nd2 ({Inferior is} 13. Bd3 $6 d5 $1 {with
comfortable play for Black. Things got out of hand after} 14. c5 $2 (14. Nd2 $5
) 14... d4 $1 15. Bd2 {and now in Zawadzka-Szczepkowska Horowska, Warsaw 2018
Black should have played} Qe7 $1 {winning a pawn, as} 16. cxb6 $2 {loses to}
Bb3+ $19) 13... d5 $6 ({Black's plan of advancing the pawn to d4 is weakening
too much the light squares and thus gives White a firm grip in the centre.
However, also after} 13... Be7 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Bd3 {White's position looks
easier to play.}) 14. O-O-O d4 15. Ne4 c5 16. Bf4 Be7 17. Bd3 h6 (17... O-O {
runs into} 18. Ng5) 18. Rde1 O-O-O ({Again, after} 18... O-O {White can go for}
19. Ng5 $1) 19. h5 $16 {Black's protected passed pawn isn't worth anything.
White has a dominant position on all sides of the board and can still make
significant progress. Although the engine does not always agree with both
players' moves it's interesting to see how Cheparinov improves his position
before opening the position on move 31.} Kb7 20. f3 a5 21. Kb1 Ka6 22. Re2 Qa4
23. b3 Qc6 24. Rhe1 Rhe8 25. Be5 Bf8 26. g4 f6 (26... Bxg4 {is met by} 27.
Nxc5+ Qxc5 28. fxg4 $18) 27. Bg3 Bf7 28. a3 Ka7 29. Qd2 Ka6 30. Rc1 Nd7 31. b4
Qb6 (31... cxb4 32. c5+ Ka7 {apperently isn't so clear...}) 32. b5+ Ka7 33. f4
f5 34. gxf5 Bxh5 35. Ree1 Bf7 36. Nf2 Rxe1 37. Rxe1 Nf6 38. Nd1 Re8 39. Nb2 Kb8
40. Na4 Qa7 41. Re5 Bd6 42. Ka1 Kc8 43. Qe1 Kd8 44. Qh1 Qb8 45. Qc6 Bxe5 46.
fxe5 Rxe5 47. Nxc5 Rxc5 48. Bxb8 Rxc6 49. bxc6 Be8 50. c7+ Kc8 51. c5 Bc6 52.
Ba6+ Bb7 53. Bb5 Nd5 54. c6 Nxc7 55. Bxc7 Bxc6 56. Bxc6 Kxc7 57. Be8 Kd6 58.
Kb2 Ke5 59. Bg6 h5 60. Bxh5 Kxf5 61. Kc2 Ke4 62. Kd2 g5 63. Bg4 Kd5 64. Kd3 Kc5
65. Bd1 Kd5 66. Be2 a4 67. Bd1 Kc5 68. Bf3 {1-0 Cheparinov-Alekseev, Batumi
2018.} *

