{[%evp 0,49,19,28,17,25,13,2,33,32,9,9,6,17,0,0,0,-16,-11,-35,-19,-62,0,-48,
-85,-59,23,58,58,70,142,106,129,151,151,170,153,196,246,302,302,284,331,350,
701,707,749,734,1647,2075,1747,2482]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 f6 9. c4 ({The critical move to
deal with 8...f6, since after} 9. exf6 {Black kingside structure remains
intact after} Nxf6 ({or even trade off queens first with} 9... Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2
Nxf6 {in both cases Black seems to have a comfortable play.})) 9... Ba6 (9...
Nb6 $6 {is a positional mistake as now White can destroy Black's pawn
structure on the kingside with} 10. exf6 $1 (10. Rh3 $2 {was once seen in an
online blitz game but after} fxe5 {I fail to see sufficient compensation for
the pawn; Nepomniachtchi-Aronian, chess.com 2017.}) 10... Qxe2+ (10... gxf6 {
is perhaps a better attempt, but in any case Black has long term problems with
his isolated f-pawn.} 11. Rh3 ({Keeping the queens on the board with} 11. Be3
$5 {might actually be an improvement.}) 11... Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 d5 13. Re3+ Kd8
14. b3 a5 $2 (14... d4 {had to be tried.}) 15. Bb2 Be7 16. Nd2 a4 17. O-O-O
axb3 18. axb3 Rg8 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Nc4 $16 {with a massive initiative for
White in Iljiushenok, I-Belyakov, Taganrog 2018.}) 11. Bxe2 gxf6 12. O-O $16 {
White not only has a better pawn structure, but Black also has to watch out
for his king despite the queens being traded off. The following blitz game
nicely illustrates White's attacking potential:} Ba6 $2 {the bishop is so much
misplaced here.} 13. Bh5+ $1 Kd8 14. b3 Bd6 15. Nd2 Be5 16. Rb1 c5 17. Nf3 d6
18. Nxe5 fxe5 19. f4 exf4 20. Rxf4 Nd7 21. Bb2 Rf8 22. Rxf8+ Nxf8 23. Rf1 Ne6
24. Rf7 {1-0 Morozevich-Anand, Doha blitz 2016.}) 10. Rh3 $5 ({The adventurous
move why you should love to play 8.h4! A safer choice is} 10. exf6 {but then
after} Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 Nxf6 {Black is in good shape, as e.g. in Darini-Gholami
Orimi, Teheran 2017.}) 10... fxe5 (10... O-O-O 11. Ra3 Nb4 12. Ra4 ({The rook
is best placed here, as it keeps an eye on the knight on b4. After} 12. Ra5 $2
{White quickly lost grip on the position:} d5 13. a3 Bxc4 14. Qg4+ Kb8 15. Bxc4
(15. axb4 Qxe5+) 15... Qxe5+ $19 {Canda-Garcia, Bayamo 1989}) 12... Bb7 $2 ({
This is as sharp as it can get in the Mieses Variation and one single mistake
can lead to a quick disaster. After the text, Black's pieces are stuck on the
queenside. Critical is} 12... Qxe5 13. Qxe5 fxe5 14. Bg5 (14. Kd1 d5 {looks OK
for Black.}) 14... Nc2+ (14... Re8 15. Kd1 Bb7 16. a3 Na6 17. b4 {leads to a
very unusual type of position with both the rook on a4 and knight on a6 being
stuck. I would rather be White here, but it's still tricky and the position
needs to be analyzed deeper.}) 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Bxd8 Kxd8 17. Rxa6 Bc5 {
the engine jumps to 0.00 but the position is very concrete and Black needs to
be careful as his knight doesn't seem to be returning into play. On the other
hand, it's not simple for White attacking the knight. Play might continue with}
18. f3 Rf8 19. Nd2 Rf4 20. Ra5 Bb4 (20... d6 $2 {allows} 21. Rxc5 $1 dxc5 22.
g3 $18) 21. Rxe5 Rd4 22. Re2 Rxh4 {and Black seems to be holding on. But from
Black's perspective this clearly not something you would like to get as a
result of the opening, which means 10...0-0-0 is quite risky.}) (12... d5 $2 {
now fails to} 13. a3 $1 Bxc4 14. Qg4+ {followed by taking on b4. The rook on
a4 protects the pawn on b4, avoiding any sort of complications initiated with
Qxe5 and Bxb4 etc.}) (12... Qe6 $6 {doesn't offer Black full equality, e.g.}
13. Nc3 $1 (13. a3 $6 Bxc4 $13) 13... Qf5 14. g4 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 fxe5 16. Kd1 d5
17. Bg5 Rd7 18. a3 Bxc4 19. axb4 Bb3+ 20. Kc1 Bxa4 21. Rxa4 $14 {and the minor
pieces are working nicely together.}) 13. a3 Na6 14. b4 Qf7 (14... Qxe5 15.
Qxe5 fxe5 16. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Yc4c5,Yg2g3,Yf1h3,Yb1c3,Ya1d1] and
Black has been deprived of any sort of active counterplay. White has two
options: 1) either play a quick c4-c5, trying to trap the knight (which allows
Black to sacrifice a piece on c5 for a couple of pawns) or 2) Play
positionally with g3, Bh3, Nc3, Rd1 with a total grip.}) 15. Be3 Re8 (15...
fxe5 16. c5 $1 {is incredibly strong as with his 15th move, White has
prevented any counter-sacrifice on c5.} Nb8 17. Rxa7 d5 18. cxd6 Bxd6 19. Nd2
$18 {looks hopeless for Black.}) 16. c5 Nb8 ({Also after} 16... Rxe5 17. Nd2 $1
{White remains clearly on top, but not} (17. Rxa6 $6 f5 $1 18. g3 g5 $1 19.
hxg5 Bg7 {which gives Black some hope as play becomes messy.})) 17. Rxa7 Rxe5
18. Nd2 d5 19. Nb3 d4 20. Nxd4 f5 21. O-O-O Be7 (21... f4 {is beautifully be
met by} 22. Rxb7 $1 Kxb7 23. Nxc6 $18) 22. Rxb7 $1 Kxb7 23. Nxc6 $1 Nxc6 (23...
Kxc6 24. Qb5#) 24. Qb5+ Ka7 25. Rd7 {1-0 Chigaev-Pogonina, Moscow 2018.}) (
10... Nb6 11. exf6 (11. Re3 $5 f5 (11... Bxc4 $2 12. exf6 $1 $18) (11... O-O-O
$5 {might be critical.}) 12. Nd2 {with interesting play.}) 11... Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2
Bxc4 {looks playable for Black.} 13. Re3+ (13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. b3 {[%cal Yc1b2]}
Ne5 15. Re3 gxf6 16. f4 Bc5 17. fxe5 (17. Re2 $2 Bd4 $19) 17... Bxe3 18. Bxe3
fxe5 $132) 13... Be6 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Bg4 Nd5 16. Re2 O-O 17. Bxe6+ dxe6 18.
g3 $132 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7,Re6][%cal Ya8b8,Yd5b4,Ya7a5] was seen in
Cheparinov-Ernst, Caleta 2019. I tend to prefer White here, as Black has some
structural weaknesses, but on the other hand, Black is very active. Perhaps
the evaluation of the position could best be described as dynamically balanced.
}) (10... Qxe5 $2 {is of course not possible as after the queen trade the
knight on d5 is hanging.}) 11. Bg5 $1 ({Morozevich' move is a very important
contribution and revival of the variation with 8.h4. In most games, White has
proceeded with} 11. Ra3 $2 {but he is in trouble after} Nb4 $1 (11... Bxc4 $2
12. Qxc4 Qb4+ 13. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 14. Bd2 Bxa3 15. Nxa3 $16 {and White is well
coordinated.}) 12. Nc3 (12. Bg5 Qe6 13. Ra5 e4 14. Kd1 d5 15. Nd2 h6 {and
Black had great control in Kovtunenko-Yeletsky, Moscow 2018}) (12. Ra4 {
was tested in Bernotas-Demianjuk, Batumi 2018 but here I would like to improve
Black's play with} Qe6 13. Nc3 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Nc2+ 16. Kd1 Nxa1
$17 {The black knight is trapped in the corner, but it will take some moves to
pick it up. Moreover, Black is ready to play d5, Bc5, Rf8 etc. with excellent
play as the central pawns are preventing the white minor pieces from becoming
active.}) 12... Qxh4 13. g3 Qd4 14. Rxa6 Nxa6 15. Bf4 {was seen in one of the
stem games of this variation: Van der Wiel-Timman, Amsterdam 1987 and now
Black's best continuation is} Qd6 $1 {when White doesn't have sufficient
compensation for the exchange after} 16. Bxe5 Qe6 $17) 11... Nf6 (11... Qb4+ $6
12. Nd2 Bd6 (12... Qxb2 13. Rb1 Qd4 14. Rhb3 $1 {and White's pieces are
working harmoniously together.}) (12... Nf6 13. O-O-O Be7 {was played in
Tuncer-Ozer, Istanbul 2019 and now} 14. Rb3 $1 {would give White a decisive
attack, e.g.} Qa5 15. Re3 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ye2e8,Ye5a5]} d6 16. f4 $1 $18) {
White's best move here is} 13. Rb3 $1 (13. O-O-O O-O 14. Qg4 Rab8 $4 15. Rb3 $1
Qa4 16. Bh6 $1 g6 17. Qxd7 $18 {and White soon won in Morozevich-Matlakov,
Sochi blitz 2016}) 13... Qa5 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Qg4 Nf4 16. O-O-O O-O 17. Kb1 $16
{[%cal Yd2e4,Yh4h5] and White's king is safer than Black's.}) ({The odd-looking
} 11... Qd6 $5 {has a point: only when the rook reaches a3 the black queen
will go to b4!} 12. Ra3 Qb4+ 13. Nc3 (13. Nd2 $2 {now fails to} Qxb2 $19) 13...
Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Be7 {looks playable for Black as he is ready to meet} 15. Qxe5 $6
{with} O-O $1) (11... Qe6 $2 {again fails to} 12. cxd5 $18) 12. Re3 {This move
is possible now the black knight has left the centre.} O-O-O (12... d6 13. g3 (
13. Nd2 $5) 13... h6 14. Bg2 Qd7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qc2 Rb8 {was seen in
Morozevich-Sharafiev, St Petersburg 2016 and now} 17. Ra3 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra7]
[%cal Ya3a7] looks very promising for White.}) (12... Qb4+ $6 13. Nd2 d6 $2 {
was played in Khamrakulov-Sturt, chess.com INT 2019 and now} 14. Rb3 $1 Qa5 (
14... Qc5 15. Be3 Qa5 16. Ra3) 15. Ra3 Qb6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Qf3 {[%csl Ra6,
Rf6][%cal Yc4c5] and White wins.}) 13. Ra3 ({Future games should focus on} 13.
Nd2 h6 $5 (13... Qf7 {as seen in Scerbin-Petran, Budapest 2000 and now} 14. Rb3
$14 {[%cal Yg5e3]}) 14. Ra3 hxg5 15. Rxa6 {leads to sharp play, where Black
seems to be doing fine according to the engine.}) (13. Rxe5 $2 {can't be
recommended, in view of} Qb4+ 14. Nc3 Bd6 {and Black has taken over the
initiative.}) (13. Rb3 $5 {is worth investigating:} h6 (13... d5 $6 14. Nd2 $1
{looks comfortable for White.}) (13... Qe6 14. Qe3 c5 15. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gd5,
Ge4] gives White stability on the light squares; Beerdsen-Colpe, Hamburg 2018.}
) 14. Qd2 (14. Be3 $2 d5 {and the bishop on e3 is in trouble.}) 14... hxg5 15.
Qa5 d6 16. Qxa6+ Kd7 17. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ye1c1] and I would prefer to be White,
but the position remains messy.} (17. hxg5 $6 Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ye7g5,Ye4c5]}))
13... Bb7 $1 ({Better than} 13... Qb4+ $6 14. Nc3 Bb7 (14... Bxc4 $2 {leads to
a favourable ending for White after} 15. Qxc4 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxa3 17. Ba6+ Kb8
18. bxa3 Ka8 19. Rc1 $16) 15. O-O-O Bc5 {White is too greedy. He should have
played against the awkwardly placed queen. Very strong is} 16. Rb3 $1 (16. Qxe5
$2 Bxf2 17. Bf4 (17. Rb3 Qc5 $132) (17. Qf5 $5) 17... Bb6 18. Na4 Rhe8 19.
Nxb6+ Qxb6 {White has compensation for the pawn, but certainly not more. The
game is still interesting, but not from a theoretical point of view. White has
