f4 a4 18. fxe5 $2 (18. Qh5 $5 {had to be tried.}) 18... axb3 19. axb3 {and now
in Santos Latasa-Pultinevicius, Skopje 2019 Black could have obtained a
winning position had he found} Nd7 $1 {, a typical manoeuvre in the Scotch as
the knight is often misplaced on b6. For instance} 20. Qf3 Nxe5 21. Bxe5 fxe5
22. Qxc6 Qe7 23. Qxa8 $2 Ba3+ 24. Kc2 Bf5+ $19) 11... dxe5 12. Nd2 Be7 13. b3
O-O 14. Bb2 f6 15. O-O-O a5 16. f4 a4 17. Bh3 Qf7 18. Bxc8 Raxc8 19. fxe5 fxe5
20. Rhf1 Qg6 21. Qxe5 {and White has regained the pawn and retains the better
structure and more active pieces.} Bb4 $2 22. h5 Qh6 23. Rxf8+ Rxf8 24. Qxc7 a3
25. Ba1 Nc8 26. g4 Nd6 27. Qxc6 Qe3 28. Qd5+ Nf7 29. Qd4 Qg5 30. Qe4 Rd8 31.
Bd4 Nh6 32. Kc2 Nxg4 33. Qe6+ {1-0 Idani-Sasikiran, Astana 2019.}) (9. c4 $6
Nb6 (9... Ba6 $2 10. cxd5 $18) 10. Nc3 Bb4 (10... Ba6 $6 11. b3 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6]
} Bb4 12. Bb2 $1 (12. Bd2 $6 O-O 13. Rh3 f6 14. exf6 Qxf6 $17 {Darini-Ganguly,
Douglas 2018.}) 12... O-O 13. a3 Be7 14. g3 $14) 11. Bd2 {was seen in
Haussernot-Shyam, Cappelle-la-Grande 2018 and now I recommend the simple} O-O {
when I am afraid h4 isn't too useful.}) 9... d6 (9... Nb4 $6 10. Nf3 Ba6 (10...
Qg6 11. Nd4 {[%cal Ya2a3,Yh4h5]}) 11. c4 d5 $2 {went completely wrong for
Black in} (11... c5 12. a3 (12. Bf4 $2 Qf5 $19) 12... Nc6 13. Bd2 $14 {[%cal
Yd2c3,Ye1c1]}) 12. a3 Bxc4 13. Qd1 Bxf1 (13... Na6 14. b4 $36) 14. Kxf1 Na6 15.
b4 c5 $2 16. Qa4+ Kd8 17. Ng5 $1 Qg6 18. e6 Qd3+ 19. Kg1 Bd6 20. Qd7# {1-0
Morozevich-Sychev, Moscow blitz 2016}) (9... a5 10. g3 $5 {A specialty of
Dutch IM Beerdsen, as he is only one who has played this move so far (3 times!)
} (10. c4 Nb6 {transposes to the game Nakamura-Robson, see 8...a5 which has
been analysed in Chapter 14.}) 10... Ba6 11. c4 Nb6 (11... Nb4 12. Bh3 $1 f5
13. O-O $14 {[%csl Ge5]}) 12. b3 Bb4 13. Bh3 Qe7 14. O-O d5 (14... O-O $2 {
is bad, in view of} 15. Ne4 $1 Rae8 {and now in Beerdsen-Ravuri, chess.com INT
2019, White should have played} (15... Qxe5 16. Bb2 Qe7 17. Nf6+ gxf6 18. Qg4+
Kh8 19. Qg5 $18) 16. a3 $1 Bc5 (16... Qxe5 {is met by} 17. Bf4 Qxe4 18. Qxe4
Rxe4 19. axb4 $18) 17. Nxc5 Qxc5 18. a4 {[%csl Rc5,Rf8][%cal Yc1a3,Ya3f8]} d6
19. e6 Bc8 20. Ba3 Qd4 21. Bb2 Qc5 22. e7 {and White wins the exchange.}) 15.
Bb2 ({An improvement upon} 15. Nf3 $6 {which went completely wrong for White
after} O-O 16. Qc2 dxc4 17. Ng5 g6 18. Ne4 Qxe5 19. Bb2 c3 20. Nxc3 Bxf1 21.
Ne4 Bd3 22. Bxe5 Bxc2 23. Nf6+ Kh8 24. Rc1 {and now in Beerdsen-Leko, Germany
2018 Black could have consolidated his material advantage best by means of} Bf5
$1 $19) 15... a4 16. Rac1 O-O 17. Nf3 axb3 18. axb3 c5 19. e6 $1 Rae8 20. Ng5
f6 21. Nxh7 $1 Kxh7 22. Bf5+ g6 23. Qh5+ Kg8 24. Bxg6 Rd8 25. Rfe1 Bxe1 26.
Rxe1 dxc4 27. Re4 Rd5 28. Bh7+ Qxh7 29. Rg4+ Kh8 30. Bxf6+ Rxf6 31. Qe8+ {
1-0 Beerdsen-Roobol, Netherlands 2018. A model attacking game from White's
perspective!}) (9... Nf4 $6 {can best be met by} 10. Qe4 $1 Ng6 11. f4 $1 d5
12. Qa4 Bd7 13. Nf3 (13. h5 Ne7 14. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Yc1e3]}) 13... c5 14. Bb5 c6
15. Be2 Be7 16. h5 Nf8 17. Bd2 c4 {led to a disaster for Black in Dominguez
Perez-Topalov,Saint Louis 2019 and here White could have finished it off with}
18. Nd4 Qh6 19. Bg4 $18) 10. exd6 Bxd6 (10... cxd6 11. Nc4 $14) 11. Nc4 {
White has a better pawn structure, which Black should compensate with active
play and a small lead in development. Easier said than done, and hence I would
take White in such positions.} Bc5 (11... O-O $6 12. Qxe6 Bxe6 13. Nxd6 cxd6
14. Bd2 {is exactly what White has been looking for. Two bishops + better pawn
structure, e.g.} Bg4 15. f3 Rfe8+ 16. Kf2 Be6 17. c4 Nb6 18. b3 $16 {[%csl Rb6]
Aravindh-Kravtsiv, Abu Dhabi 2018.}) 12. a3 ({The b4 square is a nice outpost
for either the knight or bishop, so useful prophylactic move. For example} 12.
Bd2 O-O 13. Qxe6 Bxe6 14. Bd3 Nb4 {is fine for Black.}) 12... O-O 13. Qxe6 Bxe6
14. Bd3 {As it turns out, White isn't really able exploiting the weakness on
c6.} Rfe8 ({Decentralizing the knight looks strange:} 14... Nf6 $6 15. O-O Ng4
16. Bf4 Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Bd6 18. Bxd6 cxd6 19. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Rc6,Rd6]
Perunovic-Fressinet, Heraklio 2017.}) 15. O-O a5 ({My original analyses
concluded with} 15... Bd4 16. Rb1 $14 (16. Na5 $5 {[%csl Rc6]})) 16. Ne5 (16.
Bd2 a4 $11 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ya8b8,Yc5d4]}) 16... Bc8 17. Nc4 (17. Nxc6 $2 {
leads to problems for White after} Bb7 {[%csl Rc6]} 18. Bb5 Re6 19. Rd1 Rxc6 $1
20. Rxd5 Bxf2+ $1) 17... Be6 18. Re1 Nb6 19. Ne5 Bd5 20. Be3 Bd6 21. Bd4 c5 22.
Bc3 c4 23. Bf1 (23. Bf5 $2 Na4 $1) 23... Na4 24. Bd4 c5 25. Bxc4 Bxe5 26. Bxd5
Bxd4 27. Bc6 Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Rd8 29. Bxa4 Bxb2 $11 {Caruana-Robson, Saint Louis
2019.} *

