-41,-33,-33,-31,-33,-49,-49,-49,-34,-31,-6,0,5,-1,8,0,0,0,28,0,2,-10,-2,-12,-9,
-2,-12,-45,-37,-24,-17,-24,-26,-42,39,-16,1,1,-21,-16,-29,-15]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 a5 {Modern
opening play: a rook's pawn move should be answered with a rook's pawn move on
the other wing! On a serious note, I think Black's move is quite useful as
well. Some points: 1) White often wants to strengthen the pawn formation
a2-b3-c4 and now Black is ready to play a5-a4, opening the a-file to activate
the rook on a8.2) In some cases Black wants to develop the bishop to a6.} 9. g3
$5 {This has recently become popular thanks to the efforts of Cheparinov.} (9.
Bg5 $6 Qe6 {only helps Black completing development. After} 10. c4 $6 Bb4+ 11.
Nd2 Nb6 {the pawn on c4 is in trouble, while the bishop on g5 can easily be
chased away as well.}) (9. Nd2 {doesn't put immediate pressure on the centre
and thus gives Black a couple of moves to consider:} f6 (9... Ba6 10. Qe4 $5
Bxf1 11. Kxf1 {[%cal Yh1h3,Yd2f3,Yb2b3,Ya1e1,Yc1b2] and White's position seems
to me somewhat more pleasant to play, but perhaps it's not anything special.})
(9... Qe6 $5 {transposes to Chapter 13 which covers 8... Qe6.}) 10. Nf3 (10. c4
Nf4 $1 11. exf6 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Nxe2 13. Kxe2 d5 $36 (13... gxf6 $17)) (10. exf6
Nxf6 $11) 10... fxe5 11. Bg5 Qe6 12. Qxe5 Bb4+ {White's openingsexperiment
can't be called a success:} 13. Kd1 (13. Bd2 Qxe5+ 14. Nxe5 O-O {is fine for
Black.}) (13. c3 $2 Qxe5+ 14. Nxe5 Nxc3 $1) 13... Qxe5 14. Nxe5 O-O 15. f3 Re8
16. Nd3 Bf8 $15 {Lopez Martinez-McShane, Batumi 2018.}) (9. c4 Nb6 (9... Ba6 {
and here Morozevich has tried a couple of times} 10. Nd2 {which is examined in
the notes to 10...Ba6.} (10. g3 {transposes to 9. g3.})) 10. Nd2 ({The most
natural developing move is} 10. Nc3 {and now I think Black shouldn't hurry
with the development of the light-squared bishop, as so often the bishop is
misplaced on a6 in the Mieses Variation. The most precise continuation is} Qe6
$5 (10... a4 11. Bd2 Ba6 12. Qe4 Qe6 13. b3 axb3 (13... d5 14. exd6 cxd6 {
was tested in Van der Wiel-Wedberg, Stockholm 1987 and now} 15. Qxe6+ fxe6 16.
Be3 c5 17. Be2 $14 {would give White excellent play against the central pawns.}
) 14. axb3 Bb7 15. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {and so far we have been following
Ivanisevic-Landa, Bergamo 2017 and now interesting is} 16. Kd1 $14 {[%cal
Ye4f4,Yd1c2,Yf1d3,Yh1h3] as the white king is quite safe on c2.}) (10... Ba6 $6
11. b3 Qe6 12. Bb2 a4 13. O-O-O Bb4 14. Rh3 $1 {and White has a massive
advantage, as Black's minor pieces on the queenside are not doing well. Two
interesting games confirm the assessment:} axb3 (14... O-O 15. Ne4 axb3 16.
axb3 Kh8 {was seen in Haussernot-Unuk, Valencia 2018 when White could have
obtained a decisive advantage with} 17. Ng5 Qf5 18. Qe3 $18 {[%cal Yf1d3]}) 15.
axb3 Bb7 16. Rg3 Qh6+ 17. Kb1 O-O-O 18. Ne4 c5 19. Qg4 f6 20. exf6 Bxe4+ 21.
Qxe4 gxf6 22. Qf5 Rhf8 $4 23. Bc1 Qxh4 24. Rh3 {1-0 Sychev-Abdumalik, Moscow
2018}) 11. Rh3 $6 {was the actual move-order in Haussernot-Unuk, but now I
would recommend} (11. Bd2 Bb4 $132) (11. b3 $6 a4 $1 {now see it's useful not
to have the bishop on a6, which blocks the a-file.}) (11. Qe4 Ba6 12. b3 Bb4
13. Bd2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Qe3 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 Nd7 18. Bd4 O-O
19. Rh3 Rfc8 $132 {Parvanyan-Shevchenko, Porto Carras 2018.}) 11... d5 $1 {
with the point that White can't take on d6 in view of:} (11... Ba6 12. b3 {
likely transposes to 10...Ba6}) 12. exd6 $2 Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 Bxh3 $19) (10. g3 {
was the actual move-order of Morozevich-Dominguez, where 10...Ba6 was played.
Once again, I think it is more accurate not to commit the bishop too early and
instead play} Qe6 {with comfortable play.}) 10... Qe6 $5 {In my opinion this
is a very effective way of playing for Black, as he doesn't commit his
light-squared bishop too early.} (10... d6 $6 {this typical move might be
playable, although I am not a big fan of it. In general, after White captures
on d6, his position is easier to play thanks to a favourable pawn structure.
The following blitz game nicely illustrates how things could go wrong for
Black.} 11. exd6 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 cxd6 (12... Bxd6 $14 {is more active, but
leaves Black with long term problems.}) 13. b3 Bb7 14. Bb2 c5 15. O-O a4 16.
Rfe1 Kd8 17. Bh5 Be7 18. Rad1 axb3 19. axb3 Rf8 20. Ne4 Bxe4 21. Rxe4 g6 22.
Bf3 Ra7 23. b4 Na4 24. Ra1 Kd7 25. b5 Rfa8 26. Bg7 Nb6 27. Rae1 Nc8 28. Rf4 f5
29. Bxa8 Rxa8 30. g4 fxg4 31. Rf7 Ke8 32. Rfxe7+ Nxe7 33. Bf6 {1-0
Morozevich-Jakovenko, Moscow blitz 2016.}) (10... Ba6 11. g3 a4 (11... d5 {
If Black wants to release the tension in the centre, I don't think he should
do so with moves a5 and Ba6 included.} 12. exd6 Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 cxd6 {and now
in Nepomniachtchi-Giri, Leuven blitz 2017 simple and effective is} 14. O-O {
[%csl Ra6][%cal Yf1e1,Ye2f3,Yb2b3] with a clear edge for White.}) (11... g6 $6
12. h5 Bg7 13. f4 Rg8 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. b3 d5 {was played in
Morozevich-Kovalev,V Berlin 2015 and now} 16. Bb2 $14 {looks solid and strong.
White maintains the grip in the centre.}) 12. b3 (12. Bg2 $2 {allows} Nxc4 $1)
(12. Bh3 $5 f6 (12... Nxc4 $2 13. Nxc4 Qb4+ 14. Qd2 $1 {threatening mate on d7,
and remaining a piece up, is the point of White's 12th move.}) (12... g6 {
[%cal Yf8g7,Ye8g8] is playable for Black.}) 13. e6 d5 $2 (13... dxe6 {had to
be tried, and now White can recapture the pawn or even more ambitiously play}
14. O-O $5) 14. b3 Qd6 15. O-O Be7 {was seen in Morozevich-Ragger, Berlin
blitz 2015} 16. Bb2 $16) 12... Bb7 13. Bb2 $6 (13. Rb1 $5) 13... axb3 14. axb3
Rxa1+ 15. Bxa1 Qa3 16. Qd1 Bb4 17. Bd3 Qa2 18. Ke2 O-O 19. Qc2 Qxc2 20. Bxc2 d6
21. exd6 Re8+ 22. Kd3 {was seen in Morozevich-Dominguez Perez, Doha blitz 2016,
but here Black should have considered} c5 $1 $15) 11. Nf3 ({It looks a bit
strange transferring the knight from b1 to f3 and then recapture on d2 after
trading off the dark-squared bishop. This, in combination with the numerous
pawn, moves White usually makes in the Mieses Variation, is already a clear
indication that White's attempt to fight for an opening advantage has failed.} 
11. Qe4 Ba6 12. Bd3 Bb4 {looks comfortable for Black as well, as White has
some coordination problems, controlling pawns on c4 and e5. After} 13. b3 Bc3
14. Rb1 Qxe5 $15 {only Black can be better.}) (11. g3 Bb4 {I would prefer
Black here as well.}) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ (12... O-O $5) 13. Nxd2 O-O {
Black is more than fine and White even has to be careful not ending up in an
inferior position.} 14. O-O-O Re8 15. f4 d6 $132 {Nakamura-Robson, Saint Louis
2018.}) 9... Ba6 (9... f6 10. c4 Ba6 (10... Nb6 $6 11. exf6) 11. Nd2 fxe5 12.
b3 O-O-O 13. Ne4 (13. Bg2 $5) 13... Nf6 14. Bh3 h6 15. O-O g5 {[%csl Ra6] and
White seemed to be doing quite well in this complex position in
Cheparinov-Predke, Skopje 2019.}) (9... Nb6 $5 {was played in Idani-Sychev,
Moscow 2019, and it surpised me White opted for 10.b3 as there is no need for
that.} 10. Nd2 {[%cal Yf2f4,Yd2f3]}) 10. c4 Nb6 (10... Qc5 $6 {[%csl Rc5]} 11.
Nd2 O-O-O {Van Dael-De Schampheleire, Netherlands 2018.} 12. Bh3 $1 $36 {
[%csl Rd7][%cal Ye1g1]}) (10... f6 11. Nd2 {see 9...f6.}) 11. b3 a4 (11... d6
$6 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6]} 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. Bb2 O-O-O 14. O-O $16 {something clearly
has gone wrong for Black.} Kb8 15. Qe1 a4 16. exd6 cxd6 17. Qa5 Qc7 18. Nc3
axb3 19. axb3 Nc8 20. Qa2 Be7 21. b4 Bf6 22. b5 Qb6 23. bxc6 Bxc6 24. Bxc6 Qxc6
25. Nd5 Rd7 26. Bxf6 gxf6 27. Rfb1+ {1-0 Ter Sahakyan-Pratyusha, Montebelluna
2018.}) 12. Bg2 (12. Ba3 $5) 12... Qe6 13. O-O d5 14. Nd2 Be7 15. Nf3 Qg4 16.
Bf4 O-O 17. Qd1 axb3 18. axb3 dxc4 19. bxc4 Bxc4 20. Nd4 Qxd1 21. Rfxd1 Rxa1
22. Rxa1 Ra8 23. Rxa8+ Nxa8 24. Nxc6 $14 {[%csl Rc7] Cheparinov-Xiang, China
2018.} *

